report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with childhood onset depression with auditory hallucinosis and staring spells.
MEDICATIONS: Lithium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This patient and the parent report that the patient’s symptoms of staring and spacing have dramatically reduced at this time.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for an individual of this age with a 9 Hz, 70 V posterior dominant rhythm and posterior slow waves of youth.  LAMBDA activity is noted when the patient looks about the room.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background theta.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Of note, even prior to hyperventilation when the patient is looking about the room, when not stimulated, she seems to become drowsy with brief vertex waves followed by an alerting.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  70 to 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In contrast to her previous record, no temporal wicket was identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old, right-handed woman with epilepsy for the past nine years, last seizure 2002 without loss of consciousness.  Seizures are characterized by a few minutes of confusion preceded by an aura of smelling fish and hearing seagulls.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, well organized with a 10.5 to 11 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Comparison with this patient’s previous EEGs may be valuable to localize seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

seagulls, and a few minutes of confusion. MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness  there is a 10.5 Hz  50 mV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Very brief drowsiness is characterized  by slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.
HR: 	80 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous EEG in 2005.No epileptiform  features were identified in either study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 14-day-old female with dysmorphic features, sometimes somnolent; rule out subclinical seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Mydriacyl, Midrin, Phenylephrine check spelling

INTRODUCTION: Neonatal EEG is performed in the infant nursery using standard neonatal montages. This is an awake record in a child who is difficult to console. In addition, there is a lot of background noise, which seems to consistently alert the child.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The child is essentially awake throughout the record.  The EEG remains relatively symmetric and continuous.  During awake portions of the record, there is alpha/theta frequency activity in the record.  There are portions of the record as the child becomes drowsy with increasing amounts of frontal delta.  At the close of the record, brief sleep is identified with brush-like fast activity in the central regions.
There are rare left frontal sharp waves (2) and rare left frontal delta.

HR:  56 BPM.

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No significant focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  A child of this age may have the left frontal activity as described above.  Of note, for this infant who is described as hypersomnolent, she is irritable and the tech is unable to get her to go to sleep throughout the one-hour study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 14-year-old female with epilepsy for the past 1.5 years, non-compliant missing three days of medication and had a convulsion preceded by ocular twitching.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 20 to 40 V posterior dominant rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm followed by vertex waves and stage I sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response.  The child appears to drift off to sleep at the end of photic stimulation.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These results are identical to a previous study done15 months ago.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 18-year-old woman two months pregnant who stopped Depakote when she became pregnant.  Now with breakthrough seizures and abdominal pain.
MEDICATIONS: none?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 50 to 60 uV alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS are identified in stage II sleep.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and does not produce changes in the background.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This EEG was compared to two previous EEGs: one in 2001 and one in 2003.  Neither of these were associated with epileptiform activity.  The first EEG in 2001 was recorded one day after the initiation of Depakote, at which time it might have been possible to see the epileptiform activity.  Careful review of this patient’s other  childhood studies may be important to provide appropriate treatment in pregnancy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-year-old, right-handed male with staring spells, attention deficit disorder, mild cerebral palsy, developmental delay with delayed walking at age three.  Breach delivery, anxiety, hyperactivity, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with 50 to 70 V and age-appropriate quantities of background theta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in theta with one or two shifting asymmetries but no definite lateralization.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in amplitude of the alpha rhythm with an increase in background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record and no significant lateralizing features were seen. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with tonic-clonic seizures x 2.  Past history of epilepsy but currently on no medications, schizophrenia, and cocaine abuse as well as benzodiazepine ingestion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Trazodone, Seroquel, Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by symmetric, rhythmic theta.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving at lower and faster flash frequencies with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or using special electrodes could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.

report:

lasting minutes with postictal confusion. Past history of pulmonary emboli, bipolar
disease, migraines, benzodiazepine withdrawal, demyelination changes on the 2004
MRI, cocaine and benzodiazepine dependence.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 ·
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation or
photic stimulation. Previous tracings are not available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hertz alpha rhythm
with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Features of drowsiness
include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta. Muscle artifact was picked
up in a T4 electrode throughout the entire study.
HR: : 60-70 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. The
beta described above may be due to this patient's benzodiazepine exposure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old male/female with ADHD, sleep apnea, violent behavior, depression, Elavil overdose with agitation and violent behavior. Previously on Tegretol.
MEDICATIONS: Haldol, Midazolam, Vecuronium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing a small amount of theta. Following hyperventilation, drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
HR:  106 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this child with an overdose and additional CNS-acting medications, there is no change on this EEG despite the adjustment.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.

report:

MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 44-year-old woman with change in mental status found confused, sleepy, and with a 10-minute loss of time. Left leg weakness and pain.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Brief drowsiness is primarily characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in background beta.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort.  The patient seems to be falling asleep slightly in hyperventilation. In hyperventilation, there is a brief burst of temporal 5 to 7 Hz activity, which is less than 3 seconds in duration but is slightly irregular.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Probably normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above have essentially the characteristics of a normal variant such as rhythmic and temporal theta of drowsiness.  However, this is slightly irregular.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Probably normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy since 2002 with an aura of stuttering, shortness of breath, headache, and postictal confusion, seizure-free for the past three months.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by theta activity occasionally seen in the temporal or central regions.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  During relaxed wakefulness, the patient had occasional episodes of unilateral twitching of the left arm without impairment of awareness.  This was not associated with a change in the EEG.
HR:  106 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These features are similar to this patient’s previous EEG.  The twitching was not associated with an EEG stop correlate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy; last seizure four to five months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is some head rocking artifact picked up in the occipital region, particularly during hyperventilation.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness is characterized by some hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.

IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be valuable.  Previous EEGs were not available at this time.  These results are similar to this patient’s previous study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 5.8-year-old female with epilepsy since 7 months old, history of head injury at six months, recent immigrant from India with slight increase in seizures. Seizures are described as crossing legs, lifting up, legs and arms becomes stiff and the patient stretches over one minute.  The patient has some ability to terminate her seizures on her own.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 9.5 Hz, 75 V posterior dominant rhythm and age appropriate quantities of background theta activity, as well as a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in amplitude of the background.  In hyperventilation, on one occasion, there is occipitally predominant delta. Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is some hypersynchronous, rhythmic symmetric theta.  On rare occasions, there is also some occipitally predominant rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity in drowsiness as well.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  115 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A child of this age is permitted a small amount of occipital slowing in hyperventilation.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Comparison with previous EEGs or recording one of this patient’s typical spells may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old, right-handed gentleman with alcohol abuse and alcohol-related seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record without hyperventilation or photic stimulation.

Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and an increase in background beta.  The patient is intermittently agitated and moving about.  As a result, impedance is not optimal.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The generous beta is a non-specific finding but consideration for exposure to benzodiazepines would be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30 day-year-old female with acute respiratory failure secondary to RSV, now with arching and wandering eye movements.
MEDICATIONS: Methadone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake or asleep record for an infant who sucks her pacifier throughout the sleep state and is moving continuously while awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is of appropriate voltage for an infant of this age and is continuous with a background that includes rich delta activity, smaller amounts of theta activity, and a small amount of alpha and beta frequency activity.  There is suck artifact picked up intermittently throughout the record particularly at C3.  Reviewing the video, there is no arching identified although it is not possible to determine whether or not the child’s eye movements were recorded during the study.  As the child awakens towards the end of the record, she moves vigorously.  This produces a fair amount of artifact and the background does have an increase in some of the faster frequency activities.
HR:  150 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If indicated, a repeat tracing capturing this child’s behaviors could be performed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old, right-handed male with seizures for the past two years, past history of stroke with right hemiparesis for ten years, HIV for ten years, hepatitis C, and seizures two weeks ago associated with low Dilantin levels.  Typical seizures: clammy hands, sweating, shakiness with incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and the patient seems to be drowsy during hyperventilation with slow rolling eye movements.  Additional features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm with rhythmic central theta followed by vertex waves in stage I sleep.  In brief stage II sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles were identified.
Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response.  There appears to be LAMBDA identified with photic stimulation.  The patient also starts to drift off at the end of photic stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features are identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Correlation with this patient’s previous EEGs may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30-year-old, right-handed female with episodes of feeling as if everything becomes dark and strange lasting several seconds followed by feeling normal.  Episodes are infrequent following MVA 8/20/02 without head injury.  These symptoms occur less than one time per month.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Sleep deprived digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm in what appears to be posterior slow waves of youth.  The patient becomes quite drowsy and in drowsiness there are hypersynchronous bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontal theta and delta.  On one or two occasions, this appears to be a notch, but there is no definitive spike and slow wave activity.  Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces bursts of rhythmic, relatively symmetric high amplitude mixed theta and delta activity.  On one or two occasions this is notched, but again there is no definitive epileptiform activity.  Immediately following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is a single right temporal sharp wave.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive epileptiform features were identified in this record.  While there is some notched, rhythmic, frontal slowing, there is no definitive spike and slow wave activity.  In addition, with a single right temporal sharp wave, this must be considered artifactual rather than necessarily indicative of epileptiform activity.  To further characterize this patient’s symptoms, a follow-up study or more prolonged study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a two-week-old infant with current apnea after feeding.
MEDICATIONS: check tech sheet_.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the Neonatal Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is a drowsy record.

The background EEG is symmetric and includes the anticipated milestones for an infant of this age.  There is a mixed frequency pattern with occasional bursts of frontally predominant delta activity.  There are rare sharply contoured frontal transience.  As the child becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background delta, which demonstrates minor asymmetries.
HR:  144 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The normal developmental milestones for a child of this age are apparent and the infrequent frontal transience are within normal limits at this age.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old female with epilepsy for the past three years who presents with left facial twitching and a burning feeling on the left side of the body.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Norvasc, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the or at the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient has a transition in and out of drowsiness on multiple occasions. Features in that transition include bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant delta activity, as well as an increase in background beta with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  There are brief portions of the record with features of stage II sleep, which is fragmented and not sustained.  Features include vertex waves and spindles followed by arousal.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation is associated with a photoelectric effect, but no clear driving. Temporal wicket in the transition in and out of sleep from the left is seen.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is important, a more prolonged study capturing her spells may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 34-year-old woman with seizures since 1999, complex partial in type.  Her last seizure was two years ago in 2001.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standing 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed for only less than one minute because the patient felt uncomfortable. Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The alpha rhythm was well attenuated with eye opening. MU rhythm was identified in the central area.  Hyperventilation was performed for less than one minute.  Post-hyperventilation the patient became drowsy with slow rolling eye movements and with attenuation of the background.  In drowsiness, posterior slowing of 4 to 5 Hz activity is seen.  The posterior occipital slowing has harmonic features with the alpha activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.  The occipital slowing during drowsiness is an unusual pattern and a repeat EEG may be helpful in distinguishing between the occipital harmonic features versus a pathological pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
HISTORY:

61 y.o. female with a history of seizures.




MEDICATIONS:


Topamax




SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:




The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During very drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with fair cooperation and produces
no effect.




Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of ~60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.



The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of
epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea, and seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, there is rhythmic, 5 Hz, sharply contoured activity with a flat-top shape in the left temporal region.  This may appear in bursts lasting up to 1.5 seconds.  There is a very slight degree of variability in the activity.  Identical, 5.2 Hz activity is identified from the right in similar states.  This is also seen at the close of hyperventilation as the patient becomes drowsy.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The findings described above are most compatible with a psychomotor variant.  They have the characteristic 5 Hz activity.  On the left, there is just a touch of variability in terms of actual frequency, but the identical activity is seen on the right in the same sleep state.  To further define this, a repeat study in deeper stages of sleep could be of use, however, a previous study in stage II sleep earlier this year did not identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
HISTORY:

68 y.o. male with a history of episodic weakness and speech difficulty on
awakening from sleep, referred for routine EEG for evaluation for possible seizure disorder.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

meloxicam (MOBIC) 7.5 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

gabapentin (NEURONTIN) 400 mg capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth 3 times daily for 360 days.


VENTOLIN HFA 90 mcg/actuation inhaler,

baclofen (LIORESAL) 10 mg tablet, Take 10 mg by mouth daily.

AMLODIPINE BESYLATE (AMLODIPINE PO), Take 10 mg by mouth daily.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None




TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of low voltage 9 Hz alpha
and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior
gradient.  Alpha activity attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. A moderate amount of muscle
artifact is seen.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.





IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected

report:
History:	65yo woman who presents with a history of 2 seizures that occurred 2 years ago, since
then has been seizure free. Patient had another seizure 6/21/15 after not taking her
medications correctly.
Medications:	Neurontin, Tegretol, Oxycodone, Lipitor, Aspirin, others
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
sleep spindles and K complexes appear.  Patient is asleep throughout the majority of the recording.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and mostly asleep. Patient very rapidly
transitions to sleep and is unable to stay awake even with stimulation - please correlate clinically
with an underlying sleeping disorder.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and mostly asleep. Patient very rapidly
transitions to sleep and is unable to stay awake even with stimulation - please correlate clinically
with an underlying sleeping disorder

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Following hyperventilation as the patient becomes drowsy, there is attenuation of the alpha rhythm with a pattern of primary low voltage theta followed by vertex waves and spindles.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal, one-hour video EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal, one-hour video EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 69-year-old woman with epilepsy since 1980, currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Solumedrol, Lescol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.

Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11-11.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart
rate <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm

report:
History:	32 year old man who presents with events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	DILANTIN,  DEPAKOTE ER
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for ~25 hours from 11/3/2015 till 11/4/2015.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed
at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All
automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events

During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the
record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Summary of Findings:
No electrographic seizures
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a normal ~25-hour continuous video EEG. No clinical or electrographic seizures are present.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a normal ~25-hour continuous video EEG. No clinical or electrographic seizures are present

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old girl with new onset seizures in November 2003, and one seizure in December 2003.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and well organized for a subject of this age.  There is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient falls into light sleep, which is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Migraine headache.  Patient requires clearance for driver's license.
This is a 26-year-old woman with epilepsy at age 9, seizure-free since November 2013.  Patient experiences rusty taste in her mouth followed by exhaustion.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 24-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with impedances under 5 kilohms.  Some head rocking artifact was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm.  Prominent temporal wicket was noted.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements with rhythmic central theta.  POSTS were noted in stage 1 sleep.
At the close of the record, the patient transitions to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th EEG for this patient.  Previous studies were performed February 6, 2004, March 28, 2005, and May 7, 2013.  The 2013 study was normal as this study.  No epileptiform features were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with slurred speech, left arm numbness, and blurry vision for two days, treated with Dilantin.  Negative CT.  History of TIA and depression.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Plavix, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes an 11 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of frontocentral beta activity.  In drowsiness, there is a prominent increase in background theta with occasional vertex waves.   Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  POSTS are identified in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and elicits a brief driving response at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There was occasional snore artifact identified, and this patient was falling asleep in photic stimulation suggesting that this individual may be excessively tired.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed woman, with history of possible schizophrenia and/or hypertension with episodes of syncope since the age of 13, as well as episodic confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Elavil, Seroquel, Depakote, ASA, Amitriptyline, Pravastatin, Ranitidine
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm. The patient is quite drowsy, transitioning from wakefulness into drowsiness and then as she starts to transition into stage 2 sleep there is spontaneous arousal. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude and a small amount of slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 78bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features identified. The transitions in and out of sleep with bursts of sleep occur even during photic stimulation may occur in the context of sleep deprivation. It may also be seen in an individual who is sleepy or any other cause.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 15-year-old female with syncope versus seizures, headaches, dizziness, with loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS: Adderall.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a sleep deprived study.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and rare LAMBDA.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record.  There is brief driving as well as a photoelectric effect.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is seen primarily late in the recording with an increase in rhythmic background theta. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.

Hyperventilation produces a small amount of background slowing.

HR:  72 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up tracing with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with epilepsy for the past two years after head trauma.  The seizures begin with hand shaking and loss of consciousness, convulsive activity followed by postictal confusion.  Seizures triggered by a fall in the shower.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well-organized background with a 10 Hz symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is temporal wicket activity identified.  The wicket activity on the left is slightly higher amplitude and it is slightly irritative in its nature, but there is no definite spike or slow wave activity.  As the patient reaches deeper stages of sleep, there are vertex waves and POSTS, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained and the patient intermittently arouses from sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy and does not activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no definite epileptiform activity, although there is some suspicious activity underlying what is likely a normal variant.  To clarify this, a repeat study with more prolonged sleep would be helpful to determine if in fact there is underlying left temporal sharp activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with post-traumatic epilepsy for the past two years.  Last seizure occurred four months ago.  Seizures begin with focal motor with secondary generalization.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well organized 11 Hz, 15 to 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are intermittent wicket spikes identified more from the left than the right temporal regions, which disappear in stage II sleep.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  There is also the occurrence of benign sleep transience in this patient, as well as vertex sharp waves.
Photic stimulation activates the record at higher flash frequencies to some degree.
HR:  74 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The wicket spike activity disappears in stage II sleep, which signifies a benign variant of EEG changes. A sleep deprived EEG would be useful in order to identify latent epileptiform activity in the temporal areas.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy since age 25.  She experiences occasional auras described as a vertiginous sensation and a sensation of noise, which is followed by loss of consciousness and convulsions.
MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is 10 Hz, 25 to 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is occasional theta frequency interspersed with the background rhythm, which is more prominent during hyperventilation.   There were occasional bursts of theta noticed bifrontally without clear localization to either side during hyperventilation. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation activates the record during higher flash frequencies.
HR:  68 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. The occasional bursts of symmetric bifrontal slowing without clear lateralization noted in this record is a non-specific finding. A repeat study should be performed in six months, prior to her next follow-up visit.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 2-month-old female with new onset seizures involving the left arm and face, as well as staring.  Birth weight 8 lbs., 11 oz.
MEDICATIONS: none?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record include an awake child with a rhythmic, relatively symmetric pattern with the appearance of some 4 to 5 Hz activity in the posterior regions.  As the child goes off to sleep, there is some artifact, but there is also some fast activity in what appears to be vertex activity at CZ.  The initial record is medium amplitude for a child of this age, and the sleep record is somewhat higher amplitude; again, as the recording continues, with more beta and vertex-like activity identified in the central regions.  There are some occasional electrode pops, but no definite sharp waves are seen in this record.  The overall background is continuous and appropriately symmetric.  At the close of the record, increasing quantities of delta are seen in sleep and then there is what is probably early spindle-like activity in the central regions.
HR:  160 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There are some electrode pops, but no definite sharp waves.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an infant of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 75-year-old woman with a single seizure in 1989 or 2000 followed one to two years later by a right parietal stroke.  The patient had unusual symptoms with nausea and/or vomiting in association with a first seizure and had an unusual spell this past September with multiple episodes of repetitive, paroxysmal vomiting followed by several hours of confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Aggrenox, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is a one-hour EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for age with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is occasional focal slowing with isolated arrhythmic theta or delta from the right or left centrotemporal region.  This becomes a bit more prominent as the patient becomes drowsy.  Occasional EKG artifact is noted.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving, which is slightly higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the limits of normal for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: An adult of this age is permitted a small amount of temporal slowing in drowsiness.  The amplitude asymmetry of the photic stimulation is not of pathological significance and may even be seen in slightly asymmetric electrode placement.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the limits of normal for an adult of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old woman with seizures characterized by shaking of her head as she was saying yes with an episode of partial blindness for a brief period last week.

MEDICATIONS: Unknown.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is quite drowsy throughout much of the record, but in maximal wakefulness there is a well defined 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and a more diffuse distribution of the beta activity as well as wicket.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.

HR:  64 BPM. In this single channel EKG, there appears to be C-segment depression and a notched QRS complex.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform discharges were identified.  This patient appears to be somewhat excessively drowsy.  Sleep deprivation may produce the background slowing described above. The referring physician will be contacted regarding the visual loss and EKG abnormalities.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 63-year-old woman with right frontal hemangioma, daily headaches, impaired balance, and titubation of the jaw.  Uncontrolled involuntary movements with jaw shaking and altered mentation for the last 9 years.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  The patient had very prominent trembling throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the tremble artifact, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with generous, diffuse theta, and significant head rocking artifact.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in beta.  With instruction, such as asking the patient to count backwards from 10, the patient stops trembling quite so much.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for more trembling and scant driving.
Heart rate:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  EEG recording for this patient is likely normal but unfortunately, the patient was not able to stop her head trembling consistently.  In the brief sections where she was able to stop the head trembling, the EEG does appear normal.  This is the third EEG for this patient without epileptiform activity but this EEG did seem to capture much more of her clinical symptoms which are not associated with epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 13 with tonic-clonic activity, tongue biting, postictal confusion, but without incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Depakote, and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a symmetric, reactive 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central 3 to 5 Hz activity, as well as an increase in background beta.  Spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous bilateral driving response at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Although there is a vigorous driving response, there is no photo paroxysmal effect.  If indicated, additional testing may be helpful to characterize this patient’s epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old woman with seizure disorder onset at age
13.  Last seizure occurred on August 23, 2006 during sleep with generalized tonic-clonic movements, tongue biting, and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Paxil, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION  OF   THE   RECORD:   In  wakefulness,  the  background  EEG  is symmetric, continuous, but attenuated. There is excessive muscle movement artifact seen throughout the tracing.  There is a 9Hz, 15 <DV posterior dominant alpha rhythm, with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.   Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, producing an increase in the slow activity in the theta range in the frontocentral region.  Post-hyperventilation, the baseline returns to normal within two minutes. Sleep is not achieved in this tracing. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  90BPM.
IMPRESSION: Basically normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL  CORRELATION: The excessive muscle movement artifact may obscure the subtle abnormal findings. However, no focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Basically normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
History:	37 YR OLD FEMALE R HANDED SEIZURE FREE FOR 7 YRS. Stress linked LOC
with hand trembling and prolonged LOC 1998-07; recurred at funeral 9-29-14
Medications:	KEPPRA
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows
further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
flash rates  HR was 54.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2, present
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. This is the second normal EEG for this patient. The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Repeat study may
be considered if clinically indicated.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. This is the second normal EEG for this patient. The lack of epileptiform

be considered if clinically indicated

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder, hydrocephalus with a shunt in the left occipital area.  Patient has been seizure-free for over five years and is being evaluated to come off of medications.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital and birth control pills.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous and symmetric. There is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is an increased amount of diffuse beta activity.  The amplitude increased in the left frontal and temporal areas and is consistent with a breach rhythm.  Hyperventilation slightly increased the amplitude of the background.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy, which is characterized by increased theta and beta activity. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits driving, as well as LAMBDA activity.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The increased amplitude in the left frontal and temporal areas is consistent with a breach rhythm and is due to the previous procedure of a shunt. No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  LAMBDA activity is a normal variant.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 33-day-old male transferred from Episcopal with acute respiratory failure, RSV, intubated and sedated for bronchitis.  Episodes of bilateral jerking movements of the extremities without change in blood pressure or heart rate.
MEDICATIONS: Fentanyl and Versed.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and sedated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is continuous, relatively low voltage for an infant of this age.  There is a mixture of theta and delta.  There is some head rocking artifact and there are two bursts of focal slowing from the left hemisphere. Stimulation of the patient produces occasional bursts of delta and a brief increase in background theta.  The child is never completely awake.
HR:  140 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Sedated EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is reactivity and variability in the record.  There is even a suggestion of a central delta compatible with vertex activity.  In this context, the rare burst of delta from the left may represent artifact.  The pattern described above may be a manifestation of pharmacologic sedation.  If there are ongoing issues regarding involuntary movements or the child’s mental status, a follow-up study after sedative hypnotics have been eliminated may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Sedated EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old male with epilepsy since age seven; last seizure in July 2003.
MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increased the background slowing.  Following hyperventilation, the patient fell into stage I sleep, which is identified by vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits sub and supraharmonic driving.
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The patient had vigorous supraharmonic photic driving.  A follow-up EEG in the future to rule out a photoparoxysmal response may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with epilepsy since age 7.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Pravachol, and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta with vertex waves.  Spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  In this broad-chested, heavyset male, who is recorded sitting up, there are multiple arousals from sleep with some snore identified in wakefulness.  Hyperventilation is associated with a small increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep, but does elicit scant driving at faster frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second normal EEG for this individual.  The first was in 2004.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Of note, in the last EEG, the patient had harmonic and subharmonic driving, which were not seen today.  This may be due to the fact that the patient was falling asleep in photic stimulation.  Given the patient’s history of seizures during sleep and the snoring and arousals from sleep identified here, perhaps a polysomnogram should be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

hydrochlorothiazide (HYDRODIURIL) 25 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

None

Hyperventilation: Elicits an increase in amplitude of the background in this otherwise somewhat lower voltage pattern.

Photic Stimulation: Although the patient was drifting into stage II sleep, scant driving was noted
EVENTS:
There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.
HEART RATE:
A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:
This is a normal drowsy and asleep	routine EEG.	There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.
A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.	Previous EEGs are not available at this time for comparison

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a __-year-old woman with childhood measles, encephalitis, autonomic disorder, panic disorder, and complex past medical history.  Patient has spells that can be elicited by exposure to cold.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: This is a one-hour digital video EEG performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Induction of cold is also attempted.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is high amplitude, sharply contoured with a 10 Hz, 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background, as well as some head-rocking artifact.  Temporal wicket activity is seen.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  The patient and the technologist work to produce a cold-like artifact or sensation.  The patient reports that this gives her some of her symptoms, but not one of her typical spells.  The EEG around the time that the patient becomes cold actually shows that she is drifting off to sleep with vertex waves.  Stage II sleep includes high amplitude vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Sharply contoured POSTS are also identified.
HR:  58 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no definite focal or epileptiform features seen in this record.  There is prominent wicket and head-rocking artifact.  The prominent beta may be due to this patient’s medications.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a __-year-old woman with autonomic dysfunction with intermittent episodes with loss of contact with reality.  History of measles encephalitis in childhood.
MEDICATIONS: Valium, Proamatine.
INTRODUCTION: Two-hour digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized and high amplitude with a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching amplitudes up to 60 uV.  Wicket activity is identified.  A MU rhythm is seen but testing is not performed. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta followed by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces bursts of rhythmic, symmetric slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
The patient experiences an event at 10:32.  She seems to be crying.  She moves her shoulders forward and backwards and has gentle rocking movements.  At 10:33, she shakes her head from side to side.  She appears to be upset.  Testing is not performed, and this behavior ends by 10:36.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal 2-hour video EEG captured in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This patient appears to have had a spell in the EEG with involuntary movements of the arm and head rocking movements, but no EEG change.  The behavior resembles a typical sad reaction and in the absence of scalp EEG correlate, a diagnosis other than epilepsy should be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal 2-hour video EEG captured in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
HISTORY:

48 y.o. female with a history of seizure disorder, with most recent seizure in
October, referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.

clonazePAM (KLONOPIN) 0.5 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 3 times daily.


diphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) 50 mg tablet, Take 0.5 tablets by mouth 2 times daily.

montelukast (SINGULAIR) 10 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

fluconazole (DIFLUCAN) 150 mg tablet, Take 150 mg by mouth once.


cetirizine (ZYRTEC) 10 mg tablet, Take 10 mg by mouth daily.

ammonium lactate (AMLACTIN) 12 % cream, Apply  topically as needed for Dry Skin.

carbamide peroxide (DEBROX) 6.5 % otic solution, 5 drops 2 times daily.


predniSONE (DELTASONE) 20 mg tablet, Take 20 mg by mouth 2 times daily.

hydrOXYzine (ATARAX) 25 mg tablet, Take 25 mg by mouth 3 times daily as needed for Itching.



metFORMIN (GLUCOPHAGE) 500 mg tablet, 2 times daily (with meals).

famotidine (PEPCID) 20 mg tablet, Take 20 mg by mouth 2 times daily.


carisoprodol (SOMA) 350 mg tablet, Take 350 mg by mouth 4 times daily as needed for Muscle
spasms.
pioglitazone (ACTOS) 30 mg tablet, Take 45 mg by mouth daily.


traMADol (ULTRAM) 50 mg tablet, Take 50 mg by mouth every 8 hours as needed.

aspirin 81 mg EC tablet, Take 81 mg by mouth daily.

acyclovir (ZOVIRAX) 400 mg tablet, Take 400 mg by mouth 2 times daily.

INSULIN DETEMIR (LEVEMIR SC), Inject 65 Units into the skin every morning.


valsartan-hydrochlorothiazide (DIOVAN-HCT) 80-12.5 mg per tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel one hour electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic
stimulation.


EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by symmetric and reactive 20-30 uV 9-10 Hertz posterior
dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Low amplitude
frontocentral 18-30 Hz activity was seen. Moderate amounts of low amplitude muscle artifact, EKG
artifact, and occasional electrode artifact were noted.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured


No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None




ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 90 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and drowsy one hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is a normal awake and drowsy one hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a one-month-old twin born at 36 weeks by SVD, 4 lbs., 7 oz. with episodes of stiffening and staring.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using the standard, not the neonatal montage, 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Initially, this is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is continuous, relatively symmetric and includes a mixture of delta and theta, as well as some faster frequency activity.  There are some electrode placement issues.  The record is reviewed with both the neonatal montage and with standard montage. As the recording continues, the overall background has fewer artifacts and is relatively symmetric. Features of drowsiness include an increase in delta.  There is a single right temporal sharp wave identified in the record.
There are some artifacts at T5 and some positive sharp waves in that region.
The close of the record demonstrates quiet sleep, and in quiet sleep the overall background is lower voltage.  In addition, the occasional temporal sharp waves are identified in this quiet sleep pattern.
HR:  150 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the limits of normal for an infant of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A subject of this age is permitted occasional temporal sharps as identified in this record.  This EEG shows appropriate organization for an infant of this age.  There are no findings outside of the limits of normal for an infant of this gestational age. The background EEG appears to demonstrate the appropriate maturity.  If there are ongoing concerns regarding seizures, a repeat tracing in the coming weeks using the appropriate montages for an infant of this age is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the limits of normal for an infant of this age.

report:
