report:
History:	24 year old woman with a history of seizures since 10 years old.
Medications:	DEPAKOTE
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 12Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
Symmetric vertex waves appear.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is briefly performed and stopped at the patient's request, producing no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces a minimal symmetric photic
driving response.  HR is 60.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 41-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 41-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

SEX: female

DATE OF STUDY: 09/03/2015

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: Outpatient

EEG TYPE: 95819 24 minutes

EEG #: 15-1293



HISTORY:

59 y.o. female referred for routine EEG for follow up, prior seizures. Seizure free for two years, before this 2002



MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

TEGRETOL XR 400 mg 12 hr tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.

naproxen (NAPROSYN) 250 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth every

12 hours as needed.

albuterol (PROVENTIL HFA;VENTOLIN HFA) 90 mcg/actuation inhaler, Inhale 2 puffs into the lungs every 6 hours as needed for Wheezing.

amlodipine (NORVASC) 5 mg tablet, take 1 tablet by mouth once daily	Indications: High blood pressure

Cholecalciferol, Vitamin D3, 1,000 unit Tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

fluticasone-salmeterol (ADVAIR DISKUS) 500-50 mcg/dose diskus inhaler, Inhale 1 puff into the lungs every 12 hours. levothyroxine (SYNTHROID, LEVOTHROID) 75 mcg tablet, take 1 tablet by mouth once daily

montelukast (SINGULAIR) 10 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth nightly.

omeprazole (PRILOSEC) 20 mg capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth daily as needed .



losartan (COZAAR) 100 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

Indications: High blood pressure

atorvastatin (LIPITOR) 20 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily. Indications: High cholesterol



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.

SEDATION: TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) recording using the International 10-20 system with Tl/T2 electrodes was performed utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation .



EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient. Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



There are normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes present during Stage II sleep. Slow wave sleep is not captured.

No generalized slowing is present.	No focal slowing is present. EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM) :

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES :



Hyperventilation: was deferred, due to pulmonary issues Photic Stimulation: elicits minimal driving

EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

An irregular	heart rate of 96 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:



This is a normal awake-and-asleep routine EEG.	There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is the second normal awake-and-asleep routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 


This is a normal awake-and-asleep routine EEG.There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:   This  is  an  56-year-old  male  with  a  history  of  childhood epilepsy seizure free since the early 1960 until two months ago.   History of alcohol problems, depression, and cardiac problems. Patient was witnessed to have frequent right upper extremity jerks.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and unknown medication for depression.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. The patient is awake, but possibly intoxicated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is continuous with a 9Hz, posterior dominant rhythm and generous amounts of beta activity.   Intermittent right upper extremity jerks were observed on the video and involve the right upper am.  They are not associated with an EEG correlate.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the posterior dominant alpha rhythm. Stages of sleep are not achieved. Photic stimulation elicits a brief bilateral driving response.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The slightly increased amount of beta activity could be due to the affects of alcohol. No focal or epileptiform features were seen.  The patient's arm jerks appear to have a non-cerebral cause.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year-old male with a history of epilepsy since the age of 8
years with recent stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Phenytoin, Plavix, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is an awake and drowsy record. The
background EEG shows low voltage alpha rhythm of 11 Hz. There are brief periods of
wakefulness. Interment background theta is seen. The patient is drowsy during most of
the EEG with brief periods of arousal. Drowsiness is seen with slow-rolling eye
movements. Deeper stages of the sleep were seen including vertex wave K-complexes
and spindles. No sharp waves are seen.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform activity or focal features of epilepsy were
seen. Abrupt changes were seen from wakefulness to sleep which can be seen with
medication effect, postictal state, sleep deprivation. The absence of epileptiform activity
does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old female with new episodes of black-out spells with four episodes in the last month
MEDICATIONS: Birth control pills.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient had artificial hair, which impacted electrode placement.  Impedances were within range under 5,000.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 40 to 60 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye-opening.  In drowsiness, temporal wicket activity is identified bilaterally.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing a small amount of theta. Photic stimulation produces supraharmonic driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study with sleep could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	A 17-year-old  female with blackout spells beginning two years ago. 	Last episode two weeks ago with an aura of dizziness followed by a headache, lasting two to five seconds. Evaluate for possible seizures.
MEDICATIONS: 	None.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard
10/20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age. 	There is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching amplitudes up to 50 mV. 	There is small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.		New rhythm is observed but testing was not performed to confirm this. Hyperventilation was performed earlier in the record, producing an increase in amplitude. 	Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in theta and beta. 	Deeper stages of
sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response with harmonic, supraharmonic driving, and lambda.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Normal EEG in wakefulness through drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this record. 	The generous driving response described above is a normal variant. 	 If epilepsy is an important consideration, additional testing, including a record recording sleep is advised. 	The normal developmental milestones for a child of this age have been achieved.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old woman with bipolar disease, Lyme disease, and refractory epilepsy.  Last seizure a month ago with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of the EEG includes sleep with rhythmic background slowing and vertex waves in stage I, and vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS in stage II sleep.  There are occasional arousals and there is likely snore artifact.  Photic stimulation elicits both LAMBDA and driving.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The background sleepiness may be due to medications or sleep deprivation. If snoring is an issue, additional testing may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old, right-handed woman with bipolar disease, CNS Lyme, carotid pain, and epilepsy admitted with multiple episodes of staring spells and loss of time.  Diagnosed with multiple different neurologic diagnoses including epilepsy partialis continua.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is noted to be very sleepy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Throughout the vast majority of the record, the patient is in stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS. Attempts to stimulate the patient produces very brief arousals with a brief 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient is essentially asleep during hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
HR:  72 to 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This patient’s multiple CNS medications or profound sleep deprivation may account for the pattern described above.  Of note, the patient is increasingly alert at the end of the study.  In that the patient reports multiple episodes of loss of time, a sleep disturbance could produce some of the symptoms that she is experiencing.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-year-old male with staring spells three times per week and ADHD.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was to have been a sleep deprived study, which could not be accomplished.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 9 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm. IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
History:  42  yr  old  female  who  had  one  aneurysm  coil.    Patient  presented   with dizziness.
MEDICATION: Lamictal.
ACTIVATION:  Photic Stimulation and Hyperventilation.
INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed  in the lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness,  there is a 10Hz, 40uV posterior dominant  rhythm.    Breech  rhythm  is  seen  from  the  left  frontotemporal   region  with accentuation of beta activity and the left frontotemporal and frontocentral areas. Hyperventilation produces  a small  increase  in  amplitude.    Photic  stimulation  elicited driving at 1 Hz and faster flash  frequencies.   Supraharmonic  driving was more obvious from the left hemisphere but could be seen bilaterally.
HR:  60BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The breech rhythm is an anticipated finding after craniotomy.   The prominence  of the supraharmonic  driving on the left may be due to the previous  craniotomy.    No  epileptiform  features  were seen.    Additional  recording  with sleep may be necessary to capture epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta, and in stage II sleep, vertex waves and spindles are seen.  A breach rhythm is apparent in sleep, and is characterized by increasing amplitude of the fast activity from the central regions on the left.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A breach rhythm is not an abnormality.  Of note, previous EEGs have not identified epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	4-year-old child with a history of febrile
convulsions in 2003, now admitted with respiratory distress in the context of asthmatic exacerbation. Intubated in the ICU following admission on September 11, 2007.
MEDICATIONS:	Epinephrine, Methylprednisolone, Advair, Morphine
INTRODUCTION:	Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is initially very agitated and cranky. His mother is in the bed with him attempting, with limited success, to console him.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, when the child is cooperative, there is a 7 Hz, symmetric reactive posterior dominant rhythm. Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is observed in drowsiness  followed by vertex waves, K complex, and spindles. When child makes a transition to delta sleep with high amplitude delta observed in the background.
HR: 120-150 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	No focal nor epileptiform features are identified this record. None were seen in 2007. If epilepsy is an important consideration,  a repeat, more prolonged study in the lab may be helpful. The presence of delta sleep in a routine EEG may be part
of this child's sleep deficit or be associated with medications that
he had received prior to the EEG in the ICU.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman who underwent surgery with a BIER block in the right arm and began to have involuntary shuttering of the shoulders.
MEDICATIONS: Valium and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The shoulder movements occurred whenever the patient relaxed, but would disappear whenever she paid attention.  Symptoms were marked at first, and she received a small dose of benzodiazepines.  The patient received an infusion of normal saline and then an infusion of benzodiazepines in this record for these symptoms.  She complained of occasional focal sternal chest pain during the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake with a 9.5 to 10 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient had involuntary shuttering, which did not produce a great deal of artifact in the EEG.  The EEG remained interpretable throughout.  She received an infusion of saline, which did not particularly help the symptoms.  She was more focused on her chest wall discomfort.  The patient subsequently received 1 mg of Valium, which made her somewhat drowsy and the symptoms disappeared considerably. Vertex waves were seen in stage I sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving with at times supraharmonic driving.
HR:  56 to 64 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There was no EEG signature noted for this patient’s jerking events.  Of note, the administration of benzodiazepines did increase the beta activity in the background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with a history of petit mal epilepsy diagnosed at age 13 and diabetes.  Last seizure in 1975, now with severe frontal headaches (right-sided) and vertigo for two years.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Leptopril, and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is 7.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  A probable MU rhythm is seen, but testing is not performed to confirm this.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta, as well as slow rolling eye movements and mild slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing some rhythmic, higher amplitude slowing, but no epileptiform activity.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  At photic stimulation of 21 Hz, there is a single frontal burst of theta, but no definitive photoparoxysmal response.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within  normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: With a history of petit mal epilepsy in childhood in an adult, one would be looking for a generalized 3 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave discharges.  These are typically accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Unfortunately, we were not able to elicit these today.  If ongoing absence seizures are important, a repeat fasting study may be helpful.  Alternatively, one with additional hyperventilation would be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within  normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 71-year-old woman with diabetes, TIA, depression, and three years of progressive memory loss now experiencing right facial and jaw twitching, as well as right facial weakness for four months.
MEDICATIONS: Lovastatin, Lexapro, Aricept, and Fosamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with the appearance of vertex waves.  The patient drifts off to sleep easily.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Brief bilateral driving is seen.  Twitch monitor is used in a portion of the record, but there is not a great deal of twitch artifact elicited.  A MU rhythm is seen, but testing is not performed to confirm this.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The patient’s chin twitching was subtle during this study and was not associated with a change in the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:

report:

report:

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Paxil, Buspar, Famotidine, Atenolol, Methimazole
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake through stage 2 sleep record.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Ativan, antibiotics, Ibuprofen, Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is at times crying, and at other times drowsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-week-old female who had a 35-second apneic event at home with arms and legs trembling and lips turning blue.  Previous event three weeks ago.  Child evaluated at [Hospital] for identical symptoms.
MEDICATIONS: Reglan and Zantac.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a well organized pattern.  There is some rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz high amplitude synchronous activity in the posterior regions.  In some portions of the record, as the child looks about, there is a LAMBDA activity. There is more rhythmic faster theta frequency activity identified from the frontocentral regions.  Higher amplitude, hypersynchronous rhythmic 2 to 3 Hz activity is noted as the child becomes drowsy.  This hypersynchronous activity is most prominent in the posterior regions.  Spindle activity is identified in sleep with some asynchronous spindles, appropriate for age.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for some photoelectric artifact and is performed after an attempt to awaken the child.  A scant driving response is elicited.
HR:  150 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The appropriate developmental milestones have been achieved.  The asynchronous sleep spindles are normal at this age.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a six-month-old infant with a history at nine-weeks of age of reflux.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient starts out in stage II sleep with abundant vertex waves and spindles, as well as some occipital delta.  The child awakens from sleep.  There is head-rocking artifact, but the child also demonstrates LAMBDA artifact.  Photic stimulation elicits an unusually mature driving response, and the child seems to have spiky LAMBDA.  There is also some artifact picked up in the background in wakefulness as the child becomes agitated.  A well-defined 5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is noted.
HR:  126 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: It is unusual to see such a mature driving response in an infant at six months of age.  The LAMBDA can be seen.  These findings are not necessarily pathological, but may warrant additional evaluation.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:

Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The generous beta described above may be seen in anxiety, in the setting of benzodiazepine use, or as part of a normal pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:

Features of drowsiness include high amplitude occipital rhythmic delta.  The awake record is remarkable for a fair amount of movement.  There is some theta frequency activity in the posterior regions in wakefulness.
HR:  120 BPM.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 32-year-old, right-handed woman with a history of a bitemporal abnormality and frequent seizures during sleep with general shaking.  Last seizure two weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Diovan, and Verapamil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an one hour EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The alpha rhythm is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Drowsiness is characterized by temporal theta and occasional wicket.  On one occasion, in the transition to drowsiness, two small discrete right temporal sharp waves are identified.  In stage II sleep, there are vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  The stage II sleep is remarkable for single channel artifact in T6 and attenuation in the T4-F8 chain.  Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The two discrete sharp waves may represent a normal variant.  Because of the artifact described above, this study should be repeated with greater attention to electrode placement.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The T4 electrode showed sub-optimal placement.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with history of seizures since childhood, now transferred from Episcopal because of a seizure during a stress test and now having recurrent seizures of unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection, as well as seizure detection software, nurses events, patient's alarm events were all used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Patient events:  The patient had an event at 7:26 in the morning.  She pressed the alarm, laid in bed, and became unresponsive to any verbal or motor commands.  She continued to be unresponsive for about 3 minutes, after which the doctor came in and tested her.  She started crying and appeared to be slow to answer commands, but finally ended up answering commands.  She continued crying during this event.  During the entire event there was no abnormal EEG findings and remained as a normal awake EEG.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The patient's event in which she was unresponsive had no EEG correlate.  As such, it is consistent with the diagnosis of nonepileptic psychogenic event.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 43-year-old, right-handed male transferred from an outside hospital with a tonic-clonic seizure with a somewhat abnormal CSF, but normal MRI.  Evaluated for meningitis.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Acyclovir, and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is sharply contoured, almost rhythmic theta activity identified in the temporal regions left greater than right. This is accentuated by hyperventilation.  It has some of the stereotypic morphologies of a normal variant, but the frequency ranges from 3.6 to 7.1 and occurs in brief paroxysmal bursts.  The patient seems to be very drowsy, drifting off into stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered outside the range of normal due to:
The rhythmic temporal theta activity, which does not have the characteristic frequencies of a normal variant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: While the activity described above is not specifically epileptiform in nature, it renders this EEG abnormal.  Additional recording may be important to determine if this activity improves over time, or may be associated with underlying epileptiform activity.  Of note, the patient was excessively drowsy and had difficulty completing hyperventilation.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered outside the range of normal due to The rhythmic temporal theta activity, which does not have the characteristic frequencies of a normal variant.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with a frontal meningioma resection 09/06, now with a possible seizure characterized by shaking and incontinence with speech arrest lasting just seconds.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Percocet.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is drowsy and snoring throughout portions of the record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In sleep, the background EEG demonstrates a pattern with spindles, POSTS, and some vertex waves and snore artifact.  The patient arouses readily and there is a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  When hyperventilation is performed, the patient alerts briefly then drifts off to sleep.  In sleep, there is a suggestion of an amplitude asymmetry with somewhat higher activity in the left frontal region compared to the right.

HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The breach rhythm seen in sleep with slightly higher amplitude activity is compatible with a previous craniotomy.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record, hence, this is a normal EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This  is a 56-year-old  male with right-handed  weakness  and aphasia, a feeling as if he is not speaking right, and he is weak for 15 minutes.  Evaluate for complex partial epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Nexium, aspirin, Atenolol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital  video  EEG is performed  in the lab  using standard  10-20 system  of  electrode  placement  with  one  channel  of  EKG.  Photic  stimulation  was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well organized 9Hz, posterior dominant rhythm.  The activity on the left is higher amplitude than the right. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic background theta.  Vertex waves are identified in stage I sleep.  Multiple spontaneous  arousals to and from stage I sleep are observed. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response, which is symmetric.
On one or two occasions, as the patient transitions to and from sleep, there is a suggestion of disruption of faster frequency activity on the right in comparison to the left.
HR:  66BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There  is an amplitude  asymmetry  identified, with the left being higher than the right, an unanticipated finding for an individual with  a right hemiparesis  and aphasia.   There are also one or two bursts of slowing referable  to the right hemisphere raising the possibility that there may be a process in that hemisphere.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
History:	30 year old woman with a history of epilepsy since 17 years of age, who continues
to have 3-4 seizures per week.
Medications:	Depakote (patient reports non-compliance)
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 8.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is frequently noted.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-
25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is
observed.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear
diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair effort, and produces no effect.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple
flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate of ~ 60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23-year-old woman with epilepsy as a child following head
injury. Patient had her second seizure as an adult on October 7. She was talking, saw
something orange, became lightheaded, sat down, had a loss of consciousness with
tonic-clonic activity, tongue biting and urinary incontinence followed by postictal
confusion. The patient reports feeling that something was wrong for 2 weeks prior to the
episode with lightheadedness. She was experiencing tinnitus, nausea, nervousness and
episodes of daydreaming or spacing out while driving.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 12Hz, 50 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm which is higher amplitude on the left than the right but is not
outside the range of normal. The field of alpha activity on the left is also slightly more
generous. Lambda waves are observed. Features of sleep include POSTS and an
increase in beta frequency activity. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Hyperventilation produces bilateral theta.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The amplitude asymmetry itself does not make the record
abnormal, although it is unusual. Correlation with imaging, particularly with a history of
head trauma regarding cranial injury is appropriate. Continue additional recording to
characterize her epileptiform activity is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year-old woman who had had problems with her knees
buckling for the past 5 years. Requires a cane. Since February 2008, she has been
having nocturnal seizures, 3 times per night. These seizures are described as loss of
consciousness with shaking and twitching followed by headache, bipolar disease (not
clear how she could lose consciousness during a seizure when she is already asleep).
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Valium, Darvocet, Ability
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This was a 1 hour study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9-Hz 30 mV posterior
dominant rhythm. There is a scant amount of background theta observed.
Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. The patient has some eyebrow twitching. The
technologist has an EMG channel for this. During awake EEG, the patient demonstrates
facial twitching. The technologist asked the patient "Is this your typical seizure?" The
patient answered yes, this is her typical seizure. The video demonstrates a little facial
twitching which produces artifact and the EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.
The facial twitching occurs later on in the record. Features of drowsiness include
attenuation of the alpha with rhythmic background slowing. Posts are observed. Photic
stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The clinical event
recorded was not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, bilateral motor
activity was noted. This is compatible with a nonepileptic seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video-EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient has episodes during the EEG with head twitching and trembling. These are relatively prolonged and she is unresponsive during them. As they end, she remains-unresponsive but a normal awake pattern with a well-defined alpha rhythm is seen underneath this Hyperventilation actually produces a small amount of theta. Drowsiness is by slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation is associated with head rocking artifact. There is scant driving.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second normal EEG for this individual. During this EEG, the patient had a behavioral event without stealth EEG change. These findings are identical to the May 2008 EEG which also demonstrated a nonepileptic seizure.

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 06/28/16

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, awake and drowsy




HISTORY:

a 47 y.o. male with a history of episodic tingling in hands and head (last 1 mo
ago, but occur "not often"), referred for routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.



MEDICATIONS: pt unable to recall



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 8.5-9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.




Sleep is not captured


No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Patient notes that his hands feel numb after
hyperventilation.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  The patient noted that his hands felt numb after
hyperventilation; no EEG correlate other than mild diffuse background slowing (an expected finding
after hyperventilation) was seen.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.

The patient noted that his hands felt numb after hyperventilation; no EEG correlate other than mild
diffuse background slowing (an expected finding after hyperventilation) was seen.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

If clinically warranted, a recording with sleep may be helpful.





Attending Epileptologist: 

I have personally reviewed this study, and this report represents my findings and conclusions.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  The patient noted that his hands felt numb after
hyperventilation; no EEG correlate other than mild diffuse background slowing (an expected finding
after hyperventilation) was seen.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old male admitted with recurrent seizures over the past 3 weeks characterized by headache,  chest pain, dizziness. Multiple seizures this morning treated with Ativan. Past history of MVA with loss of consciousness 10 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
During this EEG the patient had a seizure. This was at 10-9-06 2006. He is lying comfortably with  a normal awake pattern. This is followed by jerking, hiccupping, and head moving from side to side. Asynchronous arm movements are noted, a little bit more so on the left arm. He turns
his head to the left, and he bounces back and forth. During the seizure a well-defined alpha
rhythm can be identified. As he rocks his head to the left, artifact is picked up on some of the scalp electrodes, but the alpha rhythm can still be seen despite the fact that he is moving about. The behavior after 43 seconds and the EEG demonstrates a normal pattern. Of note, he starts rocking his head to the right and looks to the left at the end of the event. The technologist calls the patient. He is unresponsive despite a normal awake EEG. Another event occurs at 10:10:09. He receives Ativan for the second behavior, which is not sustained. The resident comes in and examines the patient. The patient makes eye contact with the resident during the examination. By the close of the EEG he remains awake but appears more comfortable.
HR:	54-96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The 2 behaviors observed were not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, they had behavioral characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG

20 system of electrode with 1 channel of EKG.

IMPRESSION:  CEA EEG without abnormality.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  CEA EEG without abnormality.

report:
HISTORY:

62 y.o. female with a history of seizures and

extrapyramidal symptoms referred for routine EEG for


characterization of seizures.


MEDICATIONS: VALPROIC, COGENTIN, RISPERDAL, INDERAL, PROTONIX,


ROBINUL, KLONOPIN, METOPROLOL, AMLODIPINE, BACLOFEN


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the


International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and

included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.






EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a


mixture of alpha and an excess amount of bifrontal beta activity,

organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.


Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz

posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically

with eye opening.



Drowsiness and sleep are not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21

flashes per second (fps) does not produce any EEG changes.


EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 96 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake only routine EEG.  There are no clinical


or electrographic events reported or detected.

Excess beta activity may be seen in the setting of certain


medications such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake only routine EEG.


Excess beta activity may be seen in the setting of certain

medications such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of

epilepsy.


If clinically warranted, a recording with sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake only routine EEG.  There are no clinical


or electrographic events reported or detected. 
Excess beta activity may be seen in the setting of certain


medications such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old woman with previous evaluation for nonepileptic seizures, depression, and anxiety.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had multiple behavioral events for which she was able to push the button.  In the overnight recording, she had some problems with electrode artifact.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amounts of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.

Epileptiform detections:  None.

Electrographic seizures:  None.

Events:  Multiple practice push button were noted.  In addition, behavioral events were noted at 9:56 a.m., 12:39 p.m., 3:20 p.m., 8:45 a.m., and another on the morning of the 30th at 9:09.  Although, there was electrode artifact for the events on the evening of the 29th and the morning of the 30th, no epileptiform activity was noted for any of these events and all were associated with an otherwise normal EEG, despite some movement artifact.

Seizure semiology for 9:56 a.m. nodding and blinking. Similar behavioral changes were noted at 12:39 p.m. and at 3:20 p.m.  The seizure at 8:45 begins with nodding and blinking, and then jiggling from side to side.  The patient is with the nurse at the bedside.  The nurse is examining the patient who is responsive to the nurses intervention, although she is not speaking and does not appear to have recalled the event.

The event at 9:09 on the morning of the 30th was characterized by amnesia. The patient stated that she did not recall the physician, had not seen her before, although she was otherwise able to lie down new memories and asked appropriate questions.

Heart rate 72 bpm.

IMPRESSION:  This 4-day continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
1. No epileptiform discharges of any nature.
2. An otherwise normal background.
3. Multiple different behavioral spells, sometimes with staring, sometimes with psychomotor slowing, sometimes with nodding and blinking, but never with epileptiform activity, despite the clear change in patient's sensorium.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are congruent with the previous EEG monitoring, which did not identify an epileptiform characteristic to this patient's events.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This 4-day continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for 1. No epileptiform discharges of any nature. 2. An otherwise normal background. 3. Multiple different behavioral spells, sometimes with staring, sometimes with psychomotor slowing, sometimes with nodding and blinking, but never with epileptiform activity, despite the clear change in patient's sensorium.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old woman, previously evaluated at Drexel for nonepileptic seizures, abnormal MRI, recurrent events and anxiety, evaluate for seizures.  Patient reports that i if she tactile stimulation of the scalp, produces drops.  She also is aware of events with tremulousness and stress-related seizures.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG, seizure and spike detection software.

MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, topiramate, others.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
October 27 to October 28
Background:  In wakefulness, the background includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Epileptiform Detections:  None.
Patient Events:  There are 3 events at 6:51, 3:53 and 4:35.  The patient pushes the button for all of the events with the exception of 1 event when the nurse was present at 6:51.  She stares off into space, is verbally unresponsive, and does not identify a code word.  In the 1st event, she stares off into space and is poorly responsive followed by some chewing movements.  She is able to follow some commands during that event.  In the other 2 events, she demonstrates tapping movements of the right hand.  For all 3 events, the EEG demonstrates a normal background.

Heart rate 60 bpm.

INTERVAL IMPRESSION AND CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This 1st 24 hours of video EEG monitoring was remarkable for a normal background in wakefulness through stage II sleep, but with 3 events without an EEG change.  The patient demonstrated impairment of awareness with the events suggesting that these events may be part of this patient's repetitive of anxiety-related seizures (nonepileptic seizures).

October 28 to October 29, 2914: During this section of the record, the patient experienced multiple nonepileptic seizures at times: 8:45, 9:48, 4:12 p.m., 6:27 p.m., 7 p.m., 8 p.m., 10:16 p.m., and midnight.

Background:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a symmetric reactive 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs.

Interictal Epileptiform Detections:  None.

The patient described that tactile stimulation of her scalp produces the events that she experiences.  The events are experienced by the patient as being different but she is able to push the button for all events.  She is unresponsive.  She may moan, grimace and demonstrate automatisms in the right hand.  She is responsive during the events and while examined by the physician for the 8:47 a.m. event, follows commands, taking a deep breath and participating with the physical exam.  She does not recall the code word for any of the events.  She describes the events as feeling to her as if they are much different, Some of them feel to her as if she is just dropping out.  She is aware that tactile stimulation of the scalp can produce the events.

Normal EEG was  associated with all of these events.
Heart rate 66 bpm.

IMPRESSION:  This 2nd 24 hours of video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
1. Multiple events without an EEG signature but with alteration in the patient's mental status.
2. A normal background.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A25 year old male with a single seizure related to antihistamine use at age 8. Patient reports a seizure in November 2008 while taking antibiotics, Propecia, and antifungal and playing the guitar. No aura. Tonic-clonic  activity. Former premature infant with past ill-defined prenatal history.
MEDICATIONS: Propecia, Fluconazole.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed   in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and Photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, there is a 10.8 Hz alpha rhythm of
50 to 70 meg with prominent eye movement artifact such as lateral rectus artifact. In addition, there is mu activity and temporal wicket. In hyperventilation and in a handful of occasions there is a suggestion of an underlying sharp wave in the left temporal region. Unfortunately this is the same area as remarkable for significant eye movement artifact and wicket, and some of the activity described above is clearly wicket. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Photic simulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are multiple sharply contoured normal variants or artifacts including wicket and eye artifact. No definitive epileptiform features are observed. A repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG

MEDICATIONS: Cymbalta and Ambien.
INTRODUCTION: Digital and video EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard  10/20 system of electrode placement with one-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was an awake through night sleepiness record.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and night sleepiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 35-year-old male with learning disability and epilepsy.  Seizures include tonic-clonic seizures since the age of 10 with generalized shaking, yelling and dizziness.  Additional seizures include head shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan and Ambien.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically essentially acceptable 40-minute EEG with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11.5 hertz 40 mV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal and central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles were seen in stage 2 sleep.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, producing a small increase in theta as well as an increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 3rd normal EEG for this patient over a 7-year-period.  If the patient is found to have frequent seizures, additional EEG recording strategies may be employed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 37 year old right handed female with new onset tonoclonic seizures beginning April of 2009. The seizures occur in the context of stress and depression.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, there is generous beta activity noted in the background. There seems to be an artifact picked up at T5. Wicket activity is identified bilaterally and is more prominent on the left. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is starting to drift off into sleep, and there is no significant
driving response.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for:
1. Excess beta.
2. A normal variant; wicket; which is more prominent on the left.
3. Some technical issues with the placement of the T3 and T5 electrodes.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: If this individual is thought to have new onset epilepsy rather than panic attacks, a follow-up study in the lab capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested. The presence of the excess beta may be seen in the context of anxiety and stress, which would certainly be present for any individual attempting to have an EEG with 3 small boys. Please contact the lab if needed to reschedule or repeat the EEG with sleep or even 24 hours of home EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for 1. Excess beta. 2. A normal variant; wicket; which is more prominent on the left. 3. Some technical issues with the placement of the T3 and T5 electrodes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 42-year-old woman with previous left temporal bleed, tonic-clonic seizures.  Baseline left-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Lamictal, Ativan, trazodone.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with generous diffuse beta.  Supra harmonic alpha rhythm is noted on some occasions at twice the frequency of the baseline alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude.
Photic stimulation produces vigorous bilateral driving.  During photic stimulation, there is a slight amplitude asymmetry, slightly higher amplitude on the left.  There also seems to be an accentuation of faster frequency activity from the left during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an unusual, but not pathological EEG.  It is considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The alpha harmonic, present bilaterally is a normal variant.  The prominent driving response is again a normal phenomenon as is the beta frequency activity.
The slightly more vigorous supra harmonic driving noted on the left, ipsilateral to the heterotopic tissue is not necessarily pathological and may be considered within the broad range of normal possibilities of photic response.
Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  No sharp waves or spikes were noted today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an unusual, but not pathological EEG.  It is considered within normal limits.

report:
History:	25 year old woman with a history of seizures since 15 years of age.  Patient has
been seizure-free for several years.
Medications:	Zonisamide
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minutes EEG.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but
stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule
out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minutes EEG.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but
stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule
out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 2 day old female infant ready for discharge when the infant
began to have jerking and tremulousness. Mother subsequently disclosed exposure to
opioids. Delivered at 38-weeks by 3 5-year-old mother, weight 7 pounds 2 ounces.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. As the tracing opens the patient
has just been jerking. She has just received sedative hypnotic medications and is quite
lethargic.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial section of the record demonstrates a
pattern relatively typical for a term infant, slightly low voltage, with a bit of trache
alternans. There are occasional frontal temporal sharp waves noted in the record.
There are a handful of couplets of sharp waves at C4 or C3, as well as vertex activity,
but they are not associated with any involuntary movements.
As the recording continuous, tactile stimulation of the infant elicits an arousal pattern
with a bit more of a continuous rhythmic theta pattern. With tactile stimulation, the infant
has somewhat jerking movements in the legs, but none with an epileptiform pattern.
This EEG is recorded in 2 sections after equipment issues. Generous beta is noted in
the record with vertex waves.
By the end of the record, there is a suggestion of asynchronous vertex waves, but no
definitive or pathological epileptiform sharp waves In the central regions. At the end of

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 2 day old female infant ready for discharge when the infant began to have jerking and tremulousness. Mother subsequently disclosed exposure to opioids. Delivered at 38-weeks by 35-year-old mother, weight 7 pounds 2 ounces.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. As the tracing opens the patient has just been jerking. She has just received sedative hypnotic medications and is quite lethargic.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial section of the record demonstrates a pattern relatively typical for a term infant, slightly low voltage, with a bit of trache alternans. There are occasional frontal temporal sharp waves noted in the record. There are a handful of couplets of sharp waves at C4 or C3, as well as vertex activity, but they are not associated with any involuntary movements.
As the recording continuous, tactile stimulation of the infant elicits an arousal pattern with a bit more of a continuous rhythmic theta pattern. With tactile stimulation, the infant has somewhat jerking movements in the legs, but none with an epileptiform pattern.
This EEG is recorded in 2 sections after equipment issues. Generous beta is noted in the record with vertex waves.
By the end of the record, there is a suggestion of asynchronous vertex waves, but no
definitive or pathological epileptiform sharp waves In the central regions. At the end of the record, there seems to be some movement artifact while the nurse is touching the baby. The infant is carefully examined to determine if infant is trembling or not. The rhythmic theta artifact is produced, but tactile stimulation also produces an alerting response in baby.
HR: 132 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits for an infant of this gestational age who has just received reasonably large doses of sedative hypnotic medications. The appropriate developmental milestones were identified.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded. There are some sharp waves in this record, but some sharp waves are permissible for an infant of this age. The overall synchronicity is acceptable for an infant of this age. If there are any additional questions, a follow up study may be obtained as an outpatient.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits for an infant of this gestational age who has just received reasonably large doses of sedative hypnotic medications. The appropriate developmental milestones were identified.

report:

Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is present.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity
is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to
central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with poor cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a
routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
INTRODUCTION: A 47-hour long-term EEG monitoring was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal electrodes and EKG electrodes. Continued seizure detection software was utilized and supplemented by patient's activator alarm, nursing observation, and testing. The video/EEG files were reviewed on a daily basis.
BRIEF HISTORY: A 39-year-old woman with history of diabetes, asthma, and migraines, presents with history of seizure for more than 15 years not responding to multiple medications including zonisamide, Keppra, Klonopin, gabapentin, and lyrica, here for seizure classification.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The posterior dominant rhythm seem is 9 Hz with a 20 to 60 microvolts amplitude and it is reactive to eye opening. Normal frontocentral beta seen. Sleep is seen characterized by stage I, stage II and deeper stages of sleep. Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation revealed no abnormal discharges.
INTERICTAL NONEPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None.
INTERICTAL EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None.
ICTAL: Nonepileptic seizures: Two events.
SEIZURE NUMBER, DATE, AND TIME: Nonepileptic seizure #1: September 22, 2011, at 18:30. The patient presses the alarm and complains that she feels as if she starting to have a seizure. The RNs comes into the room, she is not responsive to name, verbal commands or follows motor commands. While being questioned, she sights multiple times and at times her left hand trembles and her face twitches. This lasts for about four minutes and then she slowly starts following commands. She does not remember the code word. She rapidly became alert and oriented x3.
EEG: During this episode reveals a normal awake EEG.
Seizure #2: September 23, 2011, at 21:38. The patient complained of having a right frontal headache and pressed the alarm button. As the nurse approached the patient, the patient sighted and was not responsive to verbal or motor commands. Simultaneously she would shake her head side to side. This tasted for about two minutes and then the patient slowly started moving her left arm on command and answering questions; however, she complained of a severe headache. The EEG during the event revealed a normal awake EEG.
IMPRESSION:
1. The interictal EEG reveals no abnormalities.
2. The ictal EEG reveals two events, which had no electrographic correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and sleep video-EEG. The episodes of unresponsiveness described above had no EEG correlate and are diagnostic of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION 1. The interictal EEG reveals no abnormalities. 2. The ictal EEG reveals two events, which had no electrographic correlate.

report:
HISTORY:

24 y.o. female with a history of seizures since age 13, characterized by left hand
shaking, eyes rolling back, and tongue biting lasting for 10-20 seconds. Her last seizure was in 2011.
She was referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.




MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:


levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) 750 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.

folic acid (FOLVITE) 1 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

Etonogestrel (NEXPLANON) 68 mg Implant, by Subdermal route.


UNKNOWN TO PATIENT, Take 1 capsule by mouth daily. Takes a red birth control pill daily
Indications: Pregnancy Contraception



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.





IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



A normal interictal EEG cannot exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If clinically indicated, a more
prolonged EEG or ambulatory recording may provide additional helpful information.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz 50 mV alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta. Brief fragments of stage I sleep include vertex waves, followed by arousal. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is starting to transition in and out of sleep and does not significantly activate the record. Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were observed.  Sleep deprivation might produce the changes described above.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/19/2012 to 06/20/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes.  The first is on the 19th at noon where she felt a little startled.  The second was at 10 p.m. where she felt a mini aura characterized by tingling sensation on her face.  She did not recall an episode at 5:25, although she did push the button for a tingling sensation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity.
Event time 11:22:  There is a burst of rhythmic left temporal theta delta with frequency evolution.  This is 5 seconds in duration.  There is no push button at that time.
Event time 5:25:20 p.m.:   A burst of rhythmic theta, frequency was subtle, frequency evolution lasting only 3 seconds.  Thirty seconds later the patient reports the mini-aura which she no longer recalled.
Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12- 72 – 06/20/2012 TO 06/21/2012
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a well defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is a sleep deprived record.  Around 10:00 p.m. the patient seems to be trying to stay up.  The EEG demonstrates small EPOCHS where the patient seems to be drowsy.   Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles. The data is reviewed for the clinical symptoms that the patient experienced, but no epileptiform features are identified.
HR:    66 bpm
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/21/2012 TO 06/22/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient reported an aura at 8 p.m. on the 21st.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Around 8 p.m., the patient is noted to transition in and out of stage 2 sleep, waking up and falling back asleep.  Fragments of deeper stages of sleep are noted overnight.
No electrographic seizures were identified.  The seizure and spike detector did not identify any other epileptiform abnormalities.
Event time 11:55:  The patient pushes the button at 11:56:12 stating that she feels as if she is about to have an aura.  She puts her hand to her chest and later appears to be tearful.  The EEG is awake at this time.  No epileptiform features were noted.   For her 8:00 p.m. the patient reported symptoms that her throat was closing with the seizure.

HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for 3 bursts of rhythmic, paroxysmal theta, all less than 4 seconds in duration, but with frequency evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's clinical symptoms did not appear to be associated with well-defined epileptiform abnormalities.  On one day, however, there were discharges which appear epileptiform in nature.  While this patient did not have any of her larger spells with head turning, a feeling as if her throat was closing or impairment of awareness, this record does not exclude a diagnosis and clinically, diagnosis may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

History:	25 year old woman with a history of nocturnal seizures.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is seen  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges

be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates
