report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old woman with simple partial seizures characterized by a twitch in the right eye, with pain.  The spells occur 4-5 times per day up to 10 at night and may last 1 minute in duration.
MEDICATIONS:   Keppra and Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:   Routine, 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed   This is a technically satisfactory record.
The patient began to have a seizure with facial twitching without aura at the start of the EEG
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm reaching amplitudes of 60 microvolts.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  Very brief sleep with vertex waves, spindle, and POSTS was noted. but stage 2 sleep was not sustained.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for muscle artifact, but no significant driving.
At the start of the EEG, a single, 7. 7 second burst of 6 hertz muscle activity was noted with rhythmic ocular twitching noted in the right frontal scalp electrodes, most prominent at FP2   There was no epileptiform activity associated with this and no postictal slowing was noted with it  The patient remained awake and alert during this brief bursts and simply experienced ocular twitching.
Hyperventilation produced bilateral slowing a bit more prominent in the posterior regions. Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for
1.  77 second burst of ocular twitching with 6 hertz muscle twitch artifact, otherwise normal background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were noted in this record. The 77 second burst of 6 hertz muscle twitch artifact did not have an EEG correlate. This could be seen in a simple partial seizure or a process involving the extraocular muscle itself.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is remarkable for
1.  77 second burst of ocular twitching with 6 hertz muscle twitch artifact, otherwise normal background.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old woman, survivor of abuse with recurrent episodes of eye flutter, tremulousness, dropping to the floor with shaking.  Spells last minutes to hours and are associated with prolonged postictal awareness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  A 36-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  The patient had 2 events during hyperventilation lasting approximately 1.3 and 6 minutes in duration.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 11 Hz alpha rhythm, a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity, alpha squeak, as well as lambda.  Brief drowsiness was achieved at the end of the record and was characterized by attenuation of the alpha and an increase in beta.
Photic stimulation did not produce pathological findings, but did produce a driving response.
Hyperventilation:  Hyperventilation produced 2 spells of unresponsiveness.  The patient demonstrated eye fluttering, unresponsiveness, impaired ability to recall a code word and jerking of the upper extremities and shaking.  Her companion was with her and reported that these were typical of the patient's spells and, if the patient was standing, the patient would have dropped to the floor.
The patient was examined during the spells.  Although she was unable to recall code word, she demonstrated soft protective movements.  A normal alpha rhythm was noted when she stopped fluttering in her eyes.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This outpatient EEG demonstrated 2 behavioral events with typical clinical characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure and with a normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are typical of those seen in nonepileptic seizures.  The patient's primary neurologist was contacted immediately, and the patient was counseled today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This outpatient EEG demonstrated 2 behavioral events with typical clinical characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure and with a normal EEG.

EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.

No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.





HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and drowsy 1 hour routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.

This is a normal awake and drowsy 1 hour routine EEG.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.


No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated,
repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.

IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and drowsy 1 hour routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 44-year-old right-handed woman, treated for epilepsy in Las Vegas many years ago with Depakote, was taken off medicine, and had a recent tonic-clonic seizure, seen in the Episcopal emergency room.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was a technically acceptable 22-minute EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 20 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient is quite drowsy, starts EEG in stage 2 sleep.  Vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS were noted.  The patient transitions rapidly in and out of drowsiness.  Hyperventilation serves to activate the record and to increase the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous harmonic driving.  Heart rate 70 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This appears to be a very drowsy individual, which may play a role in the patient's recent clinical events.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 20-year-old male, status post MVA.  His face had staples, although no scar visible at present.  Femur fracture.  At the time of the accident, patient was described as having either a seizure or panic attack.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This was a technically acceptable 24-minute EEG with impedances below 5 kilo ohms with the exception of the T1 and T2 electrodes.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a relatively drowsy adult.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there was a 10 Hz alpha rhythm, which was symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Drowsiness was characterized by rhythmic background slowing as well as some rhythmic frontal slowing followed by POSTS.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but a driving response was achieved with harmonic and supra-harmonic driving.
Hyperventilation was performed with limited effort and produced primarily a drowsy pattern.
Heart rate 66-80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in the record.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be a value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
HISTORY:  A 24-year-old woman with epilepsy since high school, premenstrual seizures, 1 per year, seizure-free for the past 11 months.
INTRODUCTION:  A 1-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab, using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This EEG is technically limited by T6 electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Generous frontocentral beta activity was identified.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta with vertex waves and spindles in stage 2 sleep.
Artifact:  There is significant T6 artifact noted throughout the record, with double-phase reversal.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
Heart rate: 66-84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep, but limited by electrode artifact.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a second EEG for this patient.  The  previous study 14-1083 demonstrated frontally-predominant spike and wave activity which was not as identified today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep, but limited by electrode artifact.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old male with 8-year history of epilepsy. Describes tonic-colonic seizures with incontinence, tongue biting, and respiratory arrest.  Seizures in July and November 2014.  Patient reports sensations throughout his body on the day before his seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  One hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a technically acceptable record with impedances under 5 kilohms for most electrodes.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 hertz, 80 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted.  Patient appears to have been sleep deprived and rapidly transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation:  The patient was in stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.  Despite this, a driving response was noted at 15 hertz.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This was the 3rd normal EEG for this adult.  It did capture extensive stage 2 sleep.  If this individual continues to have frequent seizures, alternative techniques to capture epileptiform activity or a seizure may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
History:	40 year female with seizures that started several months ago.  Events are
characterized by decreased responsiveness and facial twitching.

Pt had an event in EEG lab prior to the EEG hookup. Event lasted ~ 5 minutes, no
loss of consciousness but delayed response, facial twitching and post ictal fatigue.
Patient was evaluated by a neurology resident.
Medications:	Trileptal, Valium, Paxil
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Very brief waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  Patient is asleep throughout most
of the recording.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta
activity becomes more prominent, the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent,  POSTS
(positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) appear.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to
moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed with poor cooperation (patient falls asleep) and the period of
hyperventilation is shortened.  It produces no effect.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes
per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a normal mostly asleep and briefly awake 24-minute EEG. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a normal mostly asleep and briefly awake 24-minute EEG. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

MEDICINES:  Lamictal, Valium, Paxil, Xopenex , Bactrim, metformin, Spiriva, ? opioids, others.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old woman with traumatic brain injury, cerebellar infarct, schizophrenia, chronic pain with recurrent episodes with occipital headache followed by dizziness.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, hyperventilation was deferred.  This is an awake and asleep record in a very drowsy adult.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is a 9  Hz alpha rhythm.  In drowsiness, there is an increase in background slowing with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles noted in stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting into stage 2 sleep and did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate:  78  bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and EEG monitoring will follow for this adult.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
MEDICATIONS:  Lamotrigine, multiple medications for pain, anxiety, depression, bipolar disease, including oxycodone and benzodiazepines, Lamictal, Valium, Paxil, metformin, Spiriva, many others.
HISTORY:  41 years old woman with episodes headache, dizziness and then LOC.
INTRODUCTION:  24-hour continuous video EEG monitoring was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG and seizure and spike detection software.
DATE OF STUDY:  06/22/15 to 06/23/15.
No seizures were noted by the patient, software or nursing team.  The patient reported symptoms of chronic pain and had frequent requests for pain medicine.  Typical seizures are characterized by occipital headache or dizziness and/or visual changes.
Background:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  Stage 2 sleep was characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Sleep was disrupted and the patient was awake significantly during the night.
Epileptiform Detections: None
Seizures: None
Heart rate:  84 bpm.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This 1st 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
Normal background.
Absence of epileptiform activity.
No clinical events.
DATE OF STUDY:  06/23/15 to 06/2415.
Background:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  Stage 2 sleep was characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Epileptiform Detections: None
Seizures: None
Heart rate:  84 bpm
Event at 4:04 PM: Patient was off camera for this 112 sec episode of stiffening followed by 5 min unresponsiveness after which patient then  got up and out of bed. The EEG during this event demonstrated muscle artifact during the stiffening. After the patient was placed in bed, there was a great deal of motor artifact. The patient demonstrated self protective movements at that time. The bedside physician tapped on the scalp electrodes and the EEG returned to a normal awake pattern.
IMPRESSION/ This 2 day  continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
Normal background.
Absence of epileptiform activity
Single event without EEG change and with purposeful, protective movements and no post ictal EEG changes, suggestive of Non epileptic seizure
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
These findings were reviewed with the patient who chose to terminate EEG recording the morning after the 06/23 event. The event recorded was initially off camera and differs behaviorally from the spells reported by the patient on admission.   The patient attributed the event above to “stress” .No evidence of epilepsy was found.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This 1st 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for Normal background

report:
History:	41 year old woman who presents with change in mental status.
Medications:	seroquel, clonazepam, tramadol, morphine, ativan
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11-11.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha
rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
History:	53 YR MALE WITH PMHX OF SZS. SINCE TODDLER.  PT STATES HAS BEEN
MISSING MEDS DUE TO INS ISSUES AND HAVING EPISODES OF WAKING UP
WITH BED WET. FALLING AND HEADACHES.  SEEING NEURO 7/17
Medications:	DIVALPROEX, LAMOTRIGINE,
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes, awake, asleep,
hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  HR 70
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG
does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG
does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old woman with childhood nocturnal seizures.  No other health issues.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  41-minute, digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with appropriate impedances.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Sleep was achieved.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 hertz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm, which was symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Lateral rectus eye movement artifact was noted.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements with rhythmic central theta, and POSTS.  Brief stage 2 sleep included spindles.  Sleep was sustained during the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and did not significantly activate the record.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation, but a vigorous driving response was achieved.
Heart rate 55 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted in this EEG.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, but for an individual with significant nocturnal convulsions, a followup study with more sustained sleep or even an overnight study may be informative.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
History:	22 YO FEMALE HAD FIRST SZ 3 WEEKS AGO.W/ LOC, ONSET " FELT LIKE AN
ANXIETY ATTACK", LASTING ABOUT 2 - 4 MIN. PT WOKE ON THE GROUND IT
TOOK 5 - 6 MIN TO FIND BASELINE.  PT STAYED AT OSH "NAZARETH" 3 DAY,
MRI, CT, EEG, EKG.
Medications:	KEPPRA
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Limited waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Excessive symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal
over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity,
frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes
intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  No clinical or electrographic
seizures were present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
flash rates from 15 to 17 fps.  HR is 60
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and mainly asleep.  No epileptiform discharges were
present. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and mainly asleep.  No epileptiform discharges were
present. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
History:	22 YO MALE W/ HX OF SZ IN CHILDHOOD CONTROLLED WITH LUMINAL. SZ
WENT AWAY UNTIL JUST A FEW YEARS AGO WHEN THE EVENTS CAME BACK
AS GTC LASTING 5 - 8 MIN.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does
not produce any effect.  HR is 90-100.
Summary of Findings:
No photic stimulation
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a
clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide

clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

Medications:	KEPPRA, METOPROLOL, PRINIVIL, CELEXA
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 41-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Persistent unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was unresponsive during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This brief EEG demonstrates an awake and drowsy record with in wakefulness a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old male with schizophrenia and epilepsy, learning disability.  The past EEGs with left frontocentral sharp transients.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, benztropine, hydroxyzine, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This adult had difficulty cooperating with testing.  Impedances were challenging and muscle artifact was difficult to eliminate.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a well organized pattern with generous beta.  An 11 Hz alpha rhythm was noted with generous, low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, a 5.6 hertz rhythmic, mid temporal theta was noted.  This may be identified unilaterally or bilaterally with most burst of 5-7 seconds in duration, some somewhat longer.
No slowing was noted following these bursts of 5.6 second activity.  The technologist was not able to test the patient during the bursts.  Afterwards, no impairment of awareness was noted.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta and may accentuate the 5.6 hertz activity.  Despite the muscle artifact, photic driving response was noted.
Heart rate 66 to 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This theta described above as the characteristics of a normal variant.  This EEG was remarkable for a significant amount of muscle artifact as well as the failure to perform testing during the discharges.  A follow-up study will be obtained to more completely evaluate this patient's cerebral pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 30-year-old woman with history of seizures since age 17, 3 per month, treated with multiple medications.  Anxiety and substance abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, topiramate, and Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This recording session was terminated early when the patient insisted on smoking in the room, unplugged the equipment and demanded to leave.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
Background:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS.  The patient was relatively drowsy.  Stage 2 sleep included spindles. Recording was discontinued at 4:51 PM by the patient.
Event: 12:10:49 PM  The patient was awake.  Her partner was in the room.  She had an episode of speech arrest with head turning away from the clinicians. EEG demonstrated an awake pattern. No epileptiform features were noted.  After the partner left, the patient was noted to cry and then drifted off to sleep by 12:37.
Seizures: none
Epileptiform Activity: none
Heart rate 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th normal EEG for this adult.  No epileptiform features were noted.  At least 1 clinical event was captured, although it was not seizure with motor activity.  This individual is thought to have epilepsy, alternative management strategies may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  It is a routine 20-minute EEG with acceptable impedances, aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is very drowsy throughout the EEG, but in maximal wakefulness there is 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  As he becomes drowsy, there is prominent theta within the frontal regions.  The patient was feeling asleep during photic stimulation, which still elicited harmonic and super-harmonic photic driving. report:

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This is the 2nd normal EEG for this patient who has been seizure-free for 1-2 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  A 22-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed. aspirin EC 325 mg EC tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

None

HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.

IMPRESSION

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 21-year-old young man with history of questionable seizure during sleep and intermittent dizziness and left-sided numbness.  He was studied to rule out seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  A routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation, photic stimulation, and EKG monitoring.  In the awake resting background reveals a moderate amount of 20-30 microvolt amplitude, 9-11 Hz activity posteriorly, which attenuates with eye opening.  Low voltage frontocentral beta-activity was seen, which was bilaterally symmetric.  Moderate amount of muscle eye blink and prominent EKG artifact was seen.  The patient appeared drowsy during much of the record with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and diminished beta activity along with increased low to medium amplitude frontocentral 4-6 Hz theta.  Positive occipital sharp transients of sleep were noted (POSTs) followed by progression to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, central sleep spindles, and occasional K-complexes.  Hyperventilation produced no significant activation of the record.  Photic stimulation produced symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 62 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 21-year-old young man with history of questionable seizure during sleep and intermittent dizziness and left-sided numbness.  He was studied to rule out seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  A routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation, photic stimulation, and EKG monitoring.  In the awake resting background reveals a moderate amount of 20-30 microvolt amplitude, 9-11 Hz activity posteriorly, which attenuates with eye opening.  Low voltage frontocentral beta-activity was seen, which was bilaterally symmetric.  Moderate amount of muscle eye blink and prominent EKG artifact was seen.  The patient appeared drowsy during much of the record with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and diminished beta activity along with increased low to medium amplitude frontocentral 4-6 Hz theta.  Positive occipital sharp transients of sleep were noted (POSTs) followed by progression to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, central sleep spindles, and occasional K-complexes.  Hyperventilation produced no significant activation of the record.  Photic stimulation produced symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 62 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 31-year-old woman, who had a single tonic-clonic seizure at 3 a.m. on November 21st.  Patient states that she had been very sleep deprived.  She was able to say that she was going to have a seizure and laid herself on the floor.  She was postictal and then afterwards got up and put herself in the wheelchair.  Past history of other sleep-deprived seizures.
MEDICATIONS: No AED's
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable awake EEG for a patient who was very tense.  Minimal drowsiness was obtained.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity, and a fair amount of temporalis muscle artifact.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited minimal driving.
Heart rate 75 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and limited drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were seen.  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison.  Normal EEG, does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and limited drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 54-year-old man with previous stroke and new onset seizure over the past 2 months with loss of consciousness, urinary incontinence, and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: KEPPRA
INTRODUCTION:  A routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation, photic stimulation, EKG, and EOG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The awake resting background reveals a moderate amount of 15-20 microvolt, 9-10 Hz rhythmic activity posteriorly.  A large amount of muscle artifact and generalized low voltage 20-30 Hz beta-activity was seen.  Prominent eye blink artifact was also noted.  With drowsiness, there was initial slowing followed by attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and increasing frontocentral low to medium amplitude makes frequent theta activity.  Brief stage 2 sleep was seen with further attenuation of muscle artifact and beta and vertex waves along with very brief central sleep spindle activity.  Hyperventilation produced no significant activation of record.  Photic stimulation added no additional information.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 69 per minute with ST-T wave abnormalities.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, no others reported.
INTRODUCTION:  One hour digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  The patient was quite drowsy.

Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  75 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 2nd normal EEG for this adult.  If epilepsy is an important consideration and ambulatory record, capturing this patient's clinical symptoms may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 22-year-old male who developed epilepsy in 2006, previously evaluated, with 7 prior ambulatory EEG recordings .  Prior EEGS demonstrated 3 to 4 Hz spike and wave activity and many staring spells without an EEG correlate.  Now, the patient is aware of events with staring and blinking.
MEDICATIONS:  Zarontin, levetiracetam.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was able to push the button for all events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
February 23rd to 24th:
Background:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with abundant low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness was characterized by increase in beta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, spindles were noted in stage 2 sleep.   Sleep is fragmented and patient is primarily in lighter sleep states.
Epileptiform seizures:  None.
Pushbuttons:  Practice pushbuttons only.
Interictal epileptiform detections:  In stage 2 sleep, there is rare dyshormia noted at 4:04 and 4:27 with a question of underlying 4 Hz spike and wave superimposed upon sleep morphology with spindle.
Heart rate 78-108 BPM
IMPRESSION:  Day 1:  Remarkable for:
No events.
Dyshormia:  the only brief epileptiform activity noted only in sleep.
February 24rd to 25th:
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Zarontin, medications in reduction.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring continues for 22-year-old male with staring spells.  The patient had multiple push buttons for staring spells during this 24-hour section.
Background:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Abundant stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Of note, sleep was relatively disrupted on the 1st day, but the patient seemed to be having more extensive stage 2 sleep early in the morning on the 24th.  In stage 2 sleep, occasional beta spindles were noted.  REM sleep was noted during multiple sections of the overnight recording with multiple spontaneous brief arousals from REM sleep.  There may have been some snore artifact noted at other times, but the arousals from REM sleep were not associated with epileptiform activity or significant snoring that could be detected by the recording strategy employed.
Epileptiform seizures:  None.
Pushbuttons:  On the 24th, there were 17 push button events.  Two of these were practice pushbuttons.  These events span primarily around 12:19 p.m., but standard time from 12:07 p.m. until 1:57 p.m., and then again 3:31, 4:32, and 7:18:45.  The patient is communicative and conversing with the nurse during the blinking spells.  He is awake during all of them.  After sometime, the nursing staff does not enter for every spell, but the patient can be seen clearly involved and engaged in activities and in some cases talking on the phone.  No epileptiform features were identified with the push buttons.  The EEG consistently demonstrates a normal awake pattern, although he does have some increase in heart rate.  For the 1:57 p.m. event, the patient does demonstrate a clear change in heart rate with a somewhat irregular heart rate at the end.
Epileptiform Detections:  Rare epileptiform detections were noted exclusively in sleep in this section of the record.  They are primarily seen in stage 2 sleep and include frontally predominant 2.5 to 4 Hz spike and wave activity as well as a isolated spike and wave activity.  With review using an average reference, some of the isolated spikes demonstrate a maximum between FC and F3.
Heart rate 60 to 90 to 130 BPM bpm
IMPRESSION:  This 48 hour EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
An interictal EEG, which demonstrates spike and wave and slow spike and wave activity, at this time, exclusively in sleep, similar to the previous EEG monitoring from 2006 to 2010.
Some spike and wave activity demonstrates L FC maximum.
Multiple episodes of blinking, involuntary blinking noted and wakefulness.  No EEG change noted. Patient is awake and alert for all
On rare occasions, an irregular heart rate.
Disrupted sleep with multiple arousals from REM sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted in association with the patient staring and blinking.  The irregular heart rate was also noted without clinical symptoms and referral for Cardiology consultation may be considered.
IMPRESSION:

On rare occasions, an irregular heart rate.
Disrupted sleep with multiple arousals from REM sleep.

60 CM HEAD

Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpatient), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 12 hours from 12/15/2014 to 12/16/2014.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.    All automatically detected events
were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events	1
Description of pushbutton events
See episode description.
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse, frontally predominant 5-10uV, 18-25Hz activity is also seen.  At
the beginning of the records there is excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-7Hz activity is present.
This improves over time.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  The record commences with the
patient having an episode of irregular arm and body shaking with occasional back arching and
closed eyes. This shaking intermittently worsens in severity and then improves. The event lasts for
about 10 minutes.  There is no EEG correlate to the event.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  HR was 66
Summary of Findings:
No electrographic seizures
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The episode captured above had no EEG
correlate and is clinically consistent with a psychogenic non-epileptic event.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The episode captured above had no EEG
correlate and is clinically consistent with a psychogenic non-epileptic event

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old woman with history of aneurysm,  now with intermittent shaking spells, headaches, and feeling as if she has a lightening bolt in her head followed by a difficulty moving arm and leg.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  A 36 minute routine video EEG was performed in the lab/ using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was completed.  The patient experienced shaking spells during the EEG, which were unlike her usual spells.  During which the patient experienced multiple tremulous spells, which she states are unlike her usual seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In drowsiness, there is intermittent left temporal focal slowing with brief bursts of theta/delta
Photic stimulation was performed early in the record.  The patient reports that photic stimulation made her feel extremely uncomfortable.  It produced a normal driving response, but the patient stopped the photic stimulation because she felt unwell.  During the 19 hertz stimulation, she had an episode of shaking of the legs, unassociated with a change in the EEG.  Afterwards, she felt that she was going to throw up as is typical with 1 of her spells.  During the EEG, the patient felt that she was going to be sick at 3:27.  She did not vomit.  By 3:28, she continues to feel unwell and cannot catch her breath, but the EEG shows a normal awake pattern.
At 3:29, the patient is crying.  At 3:32, the patient reports pain and is consoled by the nurse.
The patient continues to feel unwell, but the EEG demonstrates normal awake pattern.  Patient is able to follow commands.  At 3:40, the patient has an experience where she cannot close her eyes.  EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.  The physician enters at 3:43.  EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.  At 3:50, the patient is crying and again the EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.
Heart rate: 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 36 minute EEG was remarkable for:
Multiple somatic complaints without EEG change. Normal EEG during the spells
Intermittent Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  EEG monitoring will follow to look for potential epileptiform seizures.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This 36 minute EEG was remarkable for Multiple somatic complaints without EEG change. Normal EEG during the spells
Intermittent Left temporal focal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 32-year-old woman with epilepsy.  Seizures characterized by left-sided numbness and tonic-clonic activity and tongue biting.  It began as an infant stopped and then recurred at age 20 now with 3-4 per year.  Associated with hypertension and migraine headaches.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Norvasc, and others
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically acceptable record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the overall EEG has the youthful appearance with a 70 microvolt 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, rhythmic central theta. This followed by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS in stage 2 sleep. Abundant posts were noted.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate: 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if appropriate, a more prolonged test may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 70-year-old woman, admitted to the hospital on April 10, 2015.  Multiple metastases to brain/dura/scalp admitted with unresponsiveness and seizure characterized by eyes looking left, tongue biting, and foaming at the mouth.  Prolonged status epilepticus on the morning of the 10th.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, phenytoin, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive throughout the monitoring session.
April 10th to April 11th:
This section of the EEG begins after the patient has been treated for status epilepticus and was intubated and unresponsive.  The first 24 hours of the record demonstrate diffusely slow pattern with mixed theta delta and occasional arousals with muscle artifact  Some sections of the record demonstrate a bit more arrhythmic theta than the others.
There is a bit more theta noted on the morning of April 11, 2015.
Electrographic seizures:  None.
Clinical events:  None.
Epileptiform Detections:  None significant.
April 11, 2015 to April 12, 2015:
Medications, norepinephrine, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole, Ativan, and others.
Introduction:  EEG monitoring continues.  No clinical seizures were noted.
Background:  The background demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with more of a pattern of theta and delta.  Occasional spontaneous arousals were noted.
On the 12th, there were some sections of the record noted with more rhythmic, higher amplitude delta.
There are also some triphasic waves noted.
Seizures:  None.
Epileptiform Detections:  There are some subtly defined midline vertex sharp waves noted.  These differ from normal sleep morphologies.  They do not evolve, but during some sections of the record, they are somewhat more prominent than others.
Heart rate: irregular, 60 to 90 bpm.
April 12, 2015 to April 13, 2015:  During this section of the record, no clinical seizures were noted.  The patient remained intubated and unresponsive.
Medications, norepinephrine, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole,
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG continued to demonstrate a markedly slow pattern.  Intermittent rhythmic delta activity was noted as were triphasic waves.  Occasional spontaneous arousals were noted.
Electrographic seizures:  None.
Interictal sharp waves or spikes:  Vertex sharp waves can be identified using various montages.  There is a higher amplitude sharp wave  maximum at FZ.  In some sections of the record, it is more prominent than others.
Heart rate:  irregular, 70 to 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 72-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for,
Markedly slow background with intermittent arousals.
Absence of normal waveforms, awake and asleep.
An emerging F7 sharp wave noted, which was monitored for an extended period of time, which did not evolve into clinical or electrographic seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings were discussed with the clinical team.  The emerging sharp wave noted at FZ is thought to correlate with a metastasis in that same region in this individual with multiple cerebral metastases.  No electrographic or clinical seizures were recorded throughout the patient's prolonged recording.
__________________________
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This 72-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for,
Markedly slow background with intermittent arousals. Absence of normal waveforms, awake and asleep. An emerging F7 sharp wave noted, which was monitored for an extended period of time, which did not evolve into clinical or electrographic seizures.

sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

report:
History:	67 year old man who presents with a second convulsion.  Patient has an extensive
history of heart disease.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During brief stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and briefly asleep. The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and briefly asleep. The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old woman with 30-year history of epilepsy.  The patient has a strange feeling before seizures, which she is not otherwise able to describe.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  This is a 24-minute, technically satisfactory routine EEG with impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1 and T2 electrodes.  The EEG captures wakefulness and sleep.  The patient has some difficulty sitting still and use of fair amount of muscle noted in the background.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening with an anterior to posterior gradient.  The patient's transitions rapidly in and out of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, spindles, and then brief arousals.
Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was in stage 2 sleep.  It did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate:  78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged study may be of value.
__________________________
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.

HISTORY:

25 y.o. female with a history of previous seizures, with none for 5 years, now with
episodes of spinning, vomiting, headache and palpitations on awakening from sleep, referred for
routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.




MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:


topiramate (TOPAMAX) 25 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily for 360 days.


No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:






A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background consists symmetric and reactive 11-13 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Low amplitude anteriorly predominant beta
activity was seen. A large amount of muscle and eye blink artifact was seen throughout the recording.




During very brief periods of drowsiness, attenuation of muscle and eye blink artifact and low
amplitude symmetric frontocentral theta activity were seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
mild diffuse symmetric background slowing.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 80 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:






This is a normal awake and drowsy one hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 





This is a normal awake and drowsy one hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
HISTORY:

35 y.o. male with a history of hemophilia,

HCV, and possible seizures vs convulsive syncope referred for


routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.


MEDICATIONS:


aminocaproic acid (AMICAR) 250 mg/mL (25 %) solution,

levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2

times daily. Start one at bed for three days and then one twice a


day


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the


International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a




NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and

included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a

mixture of low amplitude alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal

beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior

gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and


reactive 10.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which

attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse

background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with


synchronous and symmetric vertex waves and sleep spindles. Slow

wave sleep was not captured.


No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180

seconds with good cooperation and produces mild diffuse symmetric

background slowing.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21


flashes per second (fps) produces bilateral symmetric photic

driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.



HEART RATE:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman with a long history of epilepsy, previous EEG monitoring in an outside hospital, now with daily seizures, which are ill-described by the patient.  She states that her neighbor noticed that they had stroke-like features with facial drooping and her left hand moving behind her body.
MEDICATIONS:  Lexapro, oxcarbazepine, topiramate, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Twenty-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, fronto-central beta.  In sleep, there is slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and then rhythmic theta, but sleep was not sustained and there is a glimpse of stage 1 sleep and then spontaneous arousals.  Hyperventilation produces rhythmic slowing in the background.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep and did not clearly identify a driving response.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This patient will undergo EEG monitoring to more completely characterize her epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm, which was symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta followed by rhythmic central theta and then brief vertex waves.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was transitioning to stage 2 sleep and produced minimal driving.
Heart rate: 60-78 bpm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 41-year-old woman with new-onset seizures, September 2014, characterized by screaming, shaking, tongue biting, and amnesia. This event followed alcohol and cocaine ingestion, and Xanax use.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Singulair, Flonase, Prilosec, and others.
INTRODUCTION: One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Mu activity was identified, but testing was not performed to confirm this. There is a small amount of underlying theta in the posterior regions bilaterally. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness appears in the transition in and out of sleep. Stage 2 sleep was characterized by spindles. There may be underlying snore arousals. Hyperventilation produced an increase in theta.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was falling asleep. There was a photic driving response noted.  In addition, rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness with a characteristic 5 Hz activity was noted during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 to 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and a brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness is a normal variant.  No definitive epileptiform features were noted.  The patient appears to be quite drowsy with frequent arousals and snoring. Clinical evaluation may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and a brief stage 2 sleep.

report: START DATE OF STUDY: 01/26/2016 at 11:24 END DATE OF STUDY: 01/28/2016 at 13:25  RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: inpatient EEG TYPE: long term monitoring   HISTORY: a 24 y.o. female with a history of migraines referred for routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events: episodes of "lost time" and loss of awareness. She had one episode of loss of consciousness culminating in this admission.  MEDICATIONS: gabapentin (NEURONTIN) 100 mg capsule, Take 2 capsules by mouth 3 times daily.  SEDATION: None  TECHNIQUE: A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   DAY 1 (1/26/2016, 11:24 - 1/27/2016, 06:00)  MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin is stopped  EEG BACKGROUND: The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.   Prominent lambda waves are seen in wakefulness.  During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.   Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric POSTS, vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was captured and normal.  No generalized slowing is present. No focal slowing is present.   EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present.  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: not performed  EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  HEART RATE: A heart rate in the 60s-80s bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  IMPRESSION: This is a normal long term video EEG. There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and asleep long term EEG. No clinical or electrographic events were reported or detected.  Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 2 (1/27/2016, 06:00 - 1/28/2016, 06:00)  MEDICATIONS: gabapentin still held  BACKGROUND: No change  GENERALIZED SLOWING: No change  FOCAL SLOWING: No change  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None  SPORADIC EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: 1/27/2016 at 10:28 Hyperventilation is performed for 3 minutes and produces mild background slowing  1/27/2016 at 10:36 Stepped photic stimulation in intervals from 1-21 flashes per second produced bilateral symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.  Additionally, patient is sleep deprived until 1/28/2016 03:00.  EVENTS:  (1) DATE AND TIME:  1/27/2016 at 20:06 EVENT TYPE: Event of unclear etiology CLINICAL: Patient complains of feeling "hot and tingly." Nurse tests her at 20:10 and she is A&Ox3, following commands.  On rounds the next morning, the patient notes that these symptoms are not her typical habitual events. EEG: No ictal epileptic EEG correlate is present DURATION: ~8 min POSTICTAL CHANGES:  No change in cerebral rhythms EKG: unchanged HR in single EKG lead  EKG: A single EKG lead captured a heart rate in the 60s-80s  DAY 2 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION This is a normal awake and asleep long term EEG.  The episode of feeling "hot and tingly" had no clinical correlate; given the duration and nature of the complaint, it is unlikely to represent a seizure.   Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 3 (1/28/2016, 06:00 - 1/28/2016, 13:25)  EMEDICATIONS: gabapentin still held  BACKGROUND: No change  GENERALIZED SLOWING: No change  FOCAL SLOWING: No change  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None  SPORADIC EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected  EKG: A single EKG lead captured a heart rate in the 60s-70s   DAY 3 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION  Normal EEG  Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  FINAL IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal video EEG.  The patient's typical habitual events were not captured and no conclusion can definitively be made as to whether or not they represent seizures.  One episode of feeling "hot and tingly" that lasted several minutes was captured on 1/27. Description:

 prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the

does not produce any effect.  HR was 66 BPM

	Excessive fast

the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

Tachycardia is seen on a single EKG lead. -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 2 (7/28/2016, 06:00 - 7/28/2016, 15:00)  INTERICTAL BACKGROUND: No change  EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  SEIZURES/EVENTS:  7/28/2016 at 08:46 - Nonepileptic behavioral event CLINICAL: Patient rouses from sleep, rubs face, then arm w/ R hand. At 08:47 he sits up, pulling on leads (at this point there is lead artifact). He leans forward. He then falls out of the left side of the bed (bedrail is up on right but not on left), hitting his head on the table. His arms are extended. A nurse comes in to stabilize him. During times of body shaking, there is movement artifact. There is no ictal cerebral correlate. EKG: HR increases up to 140s from baseline 60 -----------------------------------------------------------------  FINAL IMPRESSION:  This is an essentially normal video EEG. system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.  Bursts of rhythmic/semi-rhythmic runs of
5-6 Hz activity over the mid-temporal regions independently and synchronously for <1 second are
noted in drowsiness and most closely resemble a benign variant (rhythmic temporal theta bursts of
drowsiness / rhythmic mid temporal discharges / RMTD).





Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

1. RMTD as above



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

The bursts of theta in drowsiness are most consistent with a benign variant (RMTD).


Note the presence bradycardia in this patient with reported syncope.
IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
History:	35 year old woman who presents with episodes concerning for seizures.
Medications:	None provided
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG 
	electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates 
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over 
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.  During drowsiness, the 
background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the 
alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further 
to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with poor cooperation, and produces no effect.  
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
	No epileptiform discharges
	Sleep, stage 2
	Beta, excessive
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 28-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges 
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could 
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 28-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges 
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could 
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
HISTORY:

20 y.o. female with a history of seizure on 11/5/16 without prior history (out of
sleep, tongue biting, tearful, vomiting per mother) referred for routine EEG for characterization of
seizures.




MEDICATIONS:

No current outpatient prescriptions on file.


No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.





EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9-10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and bursts of sharply contoured theta with diffuse background slowing are seen.
Note that some of these bursts occur in close temporal proximity to definite wakeful states.



Note that there is near continuous vertical and lateral eye movement artifact seen throughout the
record, even during bursts of theta frequencies in drowsiness.  Some of these bursts are sharply
contoured and appear to have spike activity, but spike activity may represent artifact (i.e., lateral
rectus spikes).




Sleep is not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No definite epileptiform activity is present.  However, please note background has sharply contoured
theta bursts and near continuous vertical eye movement, and epileptiform activity may be "buried" in
these waveforms.




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
bilaterally synchronous slow waves.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) produced
synchronous and symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.




EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.




IMPRESSION:


This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy 1-hour EEG, though a mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction cannot be ruled out.  Please see body of report for details.  There are no clinical or
electrographic events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy 1-hour EEG, though a mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction cannot be ruled out.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

A recording capturing sleep is recommended to assess bifrontal regions as interpretation over these
regions is limited by near constant vertical and horizontal eye movement.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy 1-hour EEG, though a mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction cannot be ruled out.  Please see body of report for details.  There are no clinical or
electrographic events reported or detected.

report:
History:	31 year old woman with a history of headaches.
Medications:	Ambien, Klonopin, Latuda Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic

Description:
	
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Diffuse excess beta activity is captured. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges Sleep, stage 2
Beta, excessive
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates
