report: DATE OF STUDY: 04/25/16 RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: inpatient EEG TYPE: Intraoperative monitoring   HISTORY: a 83 y.o. MAN WHO PRESENTS FOR LEFT CEA.  MEDICATIONS: INDUCTION: LIDOCAINE, FENTANYL, VECURONIUM,,    SURGERY MEDS. SEVOFLURANE, ANCEF, EPHEDERINE, PROTAMINE  TECHNIQUE: A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   INCISION:  8:26AM             HEPARIN:  9:01AM    7000 UNITS +1000 9:58AM, +1000 10:04AM CLAMP:     9:35AM UNCLAMP:  10:43AM  EEG BACKGROUND: The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.   Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is present in the left fronto temporal region during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  As sedation is given and with changes in blood pressure a diffuse low voltage delta background can be seen intermittently.  With clamping there is no change in the background.  EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present. However, some sharply contoured frequent discharges where seen in the left anterior temporal region with an atypical field. Some where clearly artifactual.  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  HEART RATE: A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  IMPRESSION: 1. No abnormalities reported during the CEA. 2. Intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is an uneventful intraoperative 4.5 hrs EEG. There is intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific. Please note that the sharply contoured discharges are of unclear significance and may be artifactual. If there clinical concern for seizures a repeated EEG may be beneficial.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: 1. No abnormalities reported during the CEA. 2. Intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region

SEVOFLURANE, ANCEF, EPHEDERINE, PROTAMINE  TECHNIQUE: A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   INCISION:  8:26AM             HEPARIN:  9:01AM    7000 UNITS +1000 9:58AM, +1000 10:04AM CLAMP:     9:35AM UNCLAMP:  10:43AM  EEG BACKGROUND: The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.   Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is present in the left fronto temporal region during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  As sedation is given and with changes in blood pressure a diffuse low voltage delta background can be seen intermittently.  With clamping there is no change in the background.  EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present. However, some sharply contoured frequent discharges where seen in the left anterior temporal region with an atypical field. Some where clearly artifactual.  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  HEART RATE: A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  IMPRESSION: 1. No abnormalities reported during the CEA. 2. Intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is an uneventful intraoperative 4.5 hrs EEG. There is intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific. Please note that the sharply contoured discharges are of unclear significance and may be artifactual. If there clinical concern for seizures a repeated EEG may be beneficial.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: 1. No abnormalities reported during the CEA. 2. Intermittent focal slowing in the left anterior temporal region

report:
HISTORY:

58 y.o. male with a history of seizures, last occurring more than one year ago,
referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

Hydrocortisone Acetate (MEDI-CORTISONE) 1 % Cream, Apply 1 Applicatorful topically 2 times daily.

nitroGLYCERIN (NITROSTAT) 0.4 mg SL tablet, Place 0.4 mg under the tongue every 5 minutes as
needed.




No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:




A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The predominant background activity consists of generalized low voltage 20-30 Hz activity and
superimposed muscle artifact. A small amount of poorly sustained low amplitude 10-11 Hz rhythmic
activity was seen posteriorly.  During much of the tracing, the patient appeared drowsy, with
intermixed beta activity and low voltage bilateral 3-6 Hz activity.




Brief stage II sleep is accompanied by vertex waves and increased generalized slowing.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.


Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
History:	36 year old woman with a history of seizures.
	
	Hyperventilation is not perform since patient is having breathing difficulties.
Medications:	no AEDs
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake, 
	drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-9.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates 
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over 
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal 
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric 
sleep spindles and K complexes appear.  Patient very rapidly transitions from wakefulness to stage 
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) 
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
	No epileptiform discharges
	Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 23-minute EEG, awake, and mostly asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges 
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Rapid transions from 
wakefulness to stage II sleep are suggestive of an excessively drowsy patient versus an underlying 
sleep disorder - please correlate clinically.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 23-minute EEG, awake, and mostly asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges 
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Rapid transions from 
wakefulness to stage II sleep are suggestive of an excessively drowsy patient versus an underlying 
sleep disorder - please correlate clinically

TECHNIQUE:

A  Bedside portable Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and vocal stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient. Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.


EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE: A heart rate of 98 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION: This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or
electrographic events reported or detected.
